1
00:00:04,546 --> 00:00:06,548
NO CASH OR CARDS, WE ONLY ACCEPT STORIES

2
00:00:06,632 --> 00:00:10,677
"The biggest failure in the world
is not giving something even a try."

3
00:00:12,429 --> 00:00:14,973
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

4
00:00:15,265 --> 00:00:21,271
THIRD BOOK: <i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>

5
00:00:24,233 --> 00:00:25,108
I like this one.

6
00:00:25,192 --> 00:00:27,110
"Things work out
as they imagined for pros,

7
00:00:27,194 --> 00:00:29,696
while things turn out
as they feared for amateurs."

8
00:00:30,739 --> 00:00:32,574
FOOTNOTE: IT'S HIS OWN QUOTE

9
00:00:32,658 --> 00:00:34,243
The customer should be here by now.

10
00:00:34,326 --> 00:00:36,620
- Hello.
- Oh, my!

11
00:00:36,703 --> 00:00:39,623
I came here to sell a book.

12
00:00:39,706 --> 00:00:41,959
- Did you make the reservation?
- I did.

13
00:00:42,042 --> 00:00:43,126
Yes, right.

14
00:00:43,502 --> 00:00:44,419
Right.

15
00:00:44,711 --> 00:00:46,797
- Let me introduce this place.
- Okay.

16
00:00:46,880 --> 00:00:49,091
This is a space
where people are read like books,

17
00:00:49,174 --> 00:00:50,759
- I see.
- Hodong's Bookshop,

18
00:00:50,842 --> 00:00:54,179
located in the cutest neighborhood
in the world, Kangho-dong.

19
00:00:54,263 --> 00:00:56,056
- Welcome.
- Yes, thank you.

20
00:00:56,139 --> 00:00:58,475
That sounds like
the name of someone I know.

21
00:00:58,559 --> 00:01:00,435
I thought maybe you knew him.

22
00:01:00,519 --> 00:01:03,146
- That's the name of the neighborhood.
- Kangho-dong.

23
00:01:03,230 --> 00:01:05,148
- Yes.
- I see.

24
00:01:05,232 --> 00:01:07,192
The cutest neighborhood in the world is?

25
00:01:07,276 --> 00:01:09,152
- Kangho-dong town.
- Well...

26
00:01:09,236 --> 00:01:10,696
- Yes.
- No, just Kangho-dong.

27
00:01:10,779 --> 00:01:12,030
Right, of course.

28
00:01:13,532 --> 00:01:15,450
Aren't you him?

29
00:01:16,118 --> 00:01:16,994
I look like him, don't I?

30
00:01:17,077 --> 00:01:18,996
You look exactly like him.

31
00:01:19,538 --> 00:01:20,831
He has short hair, right?

32
00:01:20,914 --> 00:01:22,124
Yes, he has short hair.

33
00:01:23,166 --> 00:01:24,084
Exactly.

34
00:01:24,167 --> 00:01:26,003
I heard you guys met each other

35
00:01:26,086 --> 00:01:28,005
- on that escaping show.
- Yes.

36
00:01:28,088 --> 00:01:29,339
We escaped together.

37
00:01:29,423 --> 00:01:32,217
- He's extraordinary, you know.
- I do.

38
00:01:32,301 --> 00:01:34,553
He pretended like he didn't know
how to escape, right?

39
00:01:34,636 --> 00:01:36,471
- He was bad at it.
- But it turns out,

40
00:01:36,555 --> 00:01:38,682
- he knew all along.
- He knew all along?

41
00:01:38,765 --> 00:01:40,642
He pretended for the sake of the show.

42
00:01:40,726 --> 00:01:42,603
He's great at acting, then.

43
00:01:42,686 --> 00:01:44,688
- I was convinced.
- He's a great actor!

44
00:01:46,773 --> 00:01:49,192
- That's amazing.
- I know he has a lot of great quotes.

45
00:01:49,276 --> 00:01:50,152
He does.

46
00:01:50,235 --> 00:01:53,280
- I heard he likes to say wise things.
- All the time.

47
00:01:53,363 --> 00:01:55,574
There's a quote from him that I like.

48
00:01:55,657 --> 00:01:56,867
Which one is it?

49
00:01:56,950 --> 00:01:58,327
"We can't be..."

50
00:01:58,410 --> 00:01:59,745
Wait a second.

51
00:02:00,162 --> 00:02:01,788
"We can't be..." I got it.

52
00:02:02,164 --> 00:02:05,959
"We can't be your fence."

53
00:02:06,877 --> 00:02:09,504
Hang on. "However, we can be your ladder"?

54
00:02:09,588 --> 00:02:10,839
- Was that it?
- It's the opposite.

55
00:02:10,922 --> 00:02:12,090
Is it? I'm sorry.

56
00:02:12,174 --> 00:02:13,759
- Hold on.
- We...

57
00:02:13,842 --> 00:02:16,303
FOOTNOTE: IT'S LIKELY
"EVEN IF WE CAN'T LIFT YOU LIKE A LADDER,

58
00:02:16,386 --> 00:02:18,889
WE CAN EMBRACE YOU LIKE A FENCE"

59
00:02:19,514 --> 00:02:22,434
I'm sorry.
Like you said, he has great quotes.

60
00:02:22,517 --> 00:02:25,395
I really respect and admire him.

61
00:02:25,479 --> 00:02:27,814
A lot of his quotes speak to me.

62
00:02:27,898 --> 00:02:30,567
"I can't be a ladder,
but I can be a fence." That means--

63
00:02:30,651 --> 00:02:32,110
- Sorry, just a second.
- Yes?

64
00:02:32,778 --> 00:02:34,446
- People are watching this
- Yes.

65
00:02:34,529 --> 00:02:36,198
- on their screens.
- Right.

66
00:02:36,907 --> 00:02:38,075
What's up with your face?

67
00:02:39,076 --> 00:02:40,911
It looks unnatural.

68
00:02:40,994 --> 00:02:42,412
- My face--
- I can see it.

69
00:02:42,496 --> 00:02:44,831
Yes, my face...

70
00:02:44,915 --> 00:02:46,124
Sorry?

71
00:02:46,750 --> 00:02:48,418
- Is it noticeable?
- What?

72
00:02:48,502 --> 00:02:51,922
I get skincare treatments
from time to time.

73
00:02:52,005 --> 00:02:54,966
I think my workout yesterday flared it up.

74
00:02:55,050 --> 00:02:56,551
- Usually...
- What did you get done?

75
00:02:56,677 --> 00:03:00,555
I heard it makes your skin look good.

76
00:03:00,639 --> 00:03:03,350
- It's called Rejuran or something.
- What?

77
00:03:03,433 --> 00:03:05,852
- I heard that the procedure hurts.
- For dewy skin... Yes.

78
00:03:05,936 --> 00:03:08,105
A 2,000-YEAR-OLD'S SKIN WITHOUT TREATMENT
I sleep through it.

79
00:03:08,188 --> 00:03:11,733
I also got something done around my eyes.

80
00:03:12,109 --> 00:03:13,652
- Eye Thermage.
- Your eyes--

81
00:03:13,860 --> 00:03:14,986
STUMPED BY SKINCARE JARGON

82
00:03:15,070 --> 00:03:16,655
I'm telling you because you asked.

83
00:03:17,114 --> 00:03:18,573
Will you buy my book or not?

84
00:03:18,657 --> 00:03:19,991
- I'm here to sell a book.
- You...

85
00:03:20,075 --> 00:03:21,618
Your face just looks unnatural.

86
00:03:22,077 --> 00:03:24,913
All right, you're here
to sell a book today.

87
00:03:24,996 --> 00:03:26,623
- We have to set a price.
- Okay.

88
00:03:26,707 --> 00:03:29,710
But we don't accept cash or credit cards.

89
00:03:29,793 --> 00:03:31,211
We only accept stories.

90
00:03:31,294 --> 00:03:32,629
- Only stories?
- Yes.

91
00:03:33,255 --> 00:03:35,549
- Only stories.
- We'll get into your story

92
00:03:35,632 --> 00:03:37,175
very soon now.

93
00:03:37,259 --> 00:03:39,302
You filled in your reservation card.

94
00:03:39,386 --> 00:03:42,055
- I see that your name is Kim Dong-hyun.
- Right.

95
00:03:42,139 --> 00:03:43,515
But you changed your name.

96
00:03:43,598 --> 00:03:45,684
- It used to be Kim Bong.
- Okay.

97
00:03:45,767 --> 00:03:47,060
- Kim Bong?
- I changed it.

98
00:03:47,144 --> 00:03:49,187
- Just Bong?
- Yes, it was Kim Bong.

99
00:03:49,271 --> 00:03:50,188
Until when?

100
00:03:50,272 --> 00:03:51,898
My second year of middle school.

101
00:03:51,982 --> 00:03:54,609
In my third year of middle school,

102
00:03:54,693 --> 00:03:56,653
- my dad, who used to drink often,
- Right.

103
00:03:56,737 --> 00:03:58,029
heard from somewhere

104
00:03:58,113 --> 00:04:00,699
that I needed to change my name.

105
00:04:00,782 --> 00:04:03,493
He brought a piece of paper

106
00:04:03,577 --> 00:04:05,537
that had a bunch of letters for names.

107
00:04:05,620 --> 00:04:07,748
That's how I suddenly became
Kim Dong-hyun.

108
00:04:07,831 --> 00:04:10,333
There was
a popular catchphrase at the time.

109
00:04:10,417 --> 00:04:12,919
- "I'm Bong!"
- Yes, it was crazy.

110
00:04:13,295 --> 00:04:16,131
"I'm Bong!" and "Give me Bong Bong."

111
00:04:16,214 --> 00:04:19,259
Also, my friends would always grab me,

112
00:04:19,342 --> 00:04:21,052
and say, "Bong appétit!"

113
00:04:21,136 --> 00:04:22,387
- So--
- <i>Jjamppong</i>.

114
00:04:22,471 --> 00:04:23,930
Even Wukong's staff, Ruyi Bang.

115
00:04:24,473 --> 00:04:27,100
Anything that sounded like "Bong"
was my nickname.

116
00:04:27,184 --> 00:04:29,728
- Back when I was little.
- Was that stressful, or did you enjoy it?

117
00:04:31,271 --> 00:04:32,230
It was both.

118
00:04:32,314 --> 00:04:35,525
Anyone with a similar name

119
00:04:35,609 --> 00:04:37,110
probably went through the same.

120
00:04:37,194 --> 00:04:39,821
Now, it might not be so bad, actually.

121
00:04:39,905 --> 00:04:41,948
- It's hard to forget.
- That's true.

122
00:04:42,032 --> 00:04:45,327
Actually, my current name is too common.

123
00:04:45,410 --> 00:04:47,245
If my name were still Kim Bong,

124
00:04:47,329 --> 00:04:48,830
it would've been memorable.

125
00:04:48,914 --> 00:04:51,166
- Even abroad, in my UFC days,
- That's true.

126
00:04:51,249 --> 00:04:53,919
if they said,
"From South Korea, Bong Kim!"

127
00:04:54,002 --> 00:04:56,671
it could've hit hard,
so I kind of miss the name.

128
00:04:56,755 --> 00:04:58,089
I see.

129
00:04:58,173 --> 00:04:59,674
Let's move on to occupation.

130
00:04:59,758 --> 00:05:01,218
What did you put for that?

131
00:05:01,301 --> 00:05:03,887
I hesitated, but I wrote this.

132
00:05:03,970 --> 00:05:05,472
- You wrote TV personality.
- TV personality,

133
00:05:05,555 --> 00:05:08,058
and ex-Mixed Martial Artist.

134
00:05:08,141 --> 00:05:09,768
So are you retired now?

135
00:05:10,143 --> 00:05:12,145
- Actually, now--
- You never

136
00:05:12,229 --> 00:05:13,563
- officially retired.
- No.

137
00:05:13,647 --> 00:05:15,065
No retirement ceremony.

138
00:05:15,148 --> 00:05:17,359
- See, that's the thing.
- Okay.

139
00:05:17,442 --> 00:05:19,069
In the MMA world,

140
00:05:19,152 --> 00:05:20,320
only a few world-class pros

141
00:05:20,695 --> 00:05:23,073
have official retirement ceremonies.

142
00:05:23,156 --> 00:05:25,784
For example,
the famous fighter, Jung Chan-sung.

143
00:05:25,867 --> 00:05:27,118
- He had a ceremony.
- Right.

144
00:05:27,202 --> 00:05:28,703
- He had a retirement ceremony.
- Yes.

145
00:05:28,787 --> 00:05:31,289
If you have a big achievement like that,
you can have it.

146
00:05:31,873 --> 00:05:34,709
If people love watching your matches
and want to see more,

147
00:05:34,793 --> 00:05:37,796
you can quit while you're ahead
and still be applauded for it.

148
00:05:38,171 --> 00:05:40,966
But not a lot of fighters
can say that about themselves.

149
00:05:41,049 --> 00:05:43,802
It would be weird
if I had one out of nowhere.

150
00:05:43,885 --> 00:05:45,554
What was your world ranking?

151
00:05:45,637 --> 00:05:47,013
My highest was sixth.

152
00:05:47,097 --> 00:05:51,142
- That's a big achievement in Asian MMA.
- It was brief. Right.

153
00:05:51,226 --> 00:05:54,354
Weren't you the highest-ranking fighter
in Asia at the time?

154
00:05:54,437 --> 00:05:56,314
I was the second-highest.

155
00:05:56,398 --> 00:05:59,109
- I was tied with the highest for a bit.
- Okay.

156
00:05:59,192 --> 00:06:01,736
But the fighter who had
the same number of wins

157
00:06:01,820 --> 00:06:03,864
- went and got another win.
- I see.

158
00:06:03,947 --> 00:06:05,740
So I was second. Not even the highest.

159
00:06:05,824 --> 00:06:08,034
I know the shape you're in these days.

160
00:06:08,118 --> 00:06:09,661
- You work out a lot.
- Yes.

161
00:06:09,744 --> 00:06:11,288
Then when you have the opportunity,

162
00:06:11,371 --> 00:06:13,123
you'll be able to
step into the ring again, right?

163
00:06:13,999 --> 00:06:17,085
I think fighters have to be wary of that
and control themselves.

164
00:06:17,168 --> 00:06:19,129
You get excited seeing young fighters,

165
00:06:19,212 --> 00:06:21,047
and you want to fight, too.

166
00:06:21,131 --> 00:06:24,426
You want to feel
the sensation of victory once again.

167
00:06:24,509 --> 00:06:27,846
My biggest regret is that
I never got to enjoy that feeling.

168
00:06:27,929 --> 00:06:29,472
Back then, even when I won,

169
00:06:30,015 --> 00:06:31,391
I didn't enjoy it.

170
00:06:31,474 --> 00:06:33,310
I thought, "Why did I do so badly?"

171
00:06:33,393 --> 00:06:36,021
Every time, I apologized
and promised to do better.

172
00:06:36,104 --> 00:06:37,814
Every win was valuable.

173
00:06:38,315 --> 00:06:40,275
I'd like to actually enjoy it for once.

174
00:06:40,358 --> 00:06:41,693
- But I have to resist.
- Right.

175
00:06:41,776 --> 00:06:43,320
I really do.

176
00:06:43,904 --> 00:06:47,908
I talk to a lot of athletes
here at the bookshop.

177
00:06:47,991 --> 00:06:49,826
A lot of them have regrets

178
00:06:49,910 --> 00:06:51,620
about not enjoying it.

179
00:06:52,037 --> 00:06:54,664
But even if they went back in time,

180
00:06:55,081 --> 00:06:57,709
being able to enjoy it would be...

181
00:06:57,792 --> 00:06:58,919
- It's hard.
- It is.

182
00:06:59,002 --> 00:07:01,212
- It's not easy to think that way.
- That's true.

183
00:07:01,630 --> 00:07:03,548
Were you an athlete? You know so well.

184
00:07:03,632 --> 00:07:06,384
I was once a <i>ssireum</i> wrestler.

185
00:07:06,468 --> 00:07:08,386
- Were you, really?
- Yes.

186
00:07:08,470 --> 00:07:10,430
- Really?
- I was a <i>ssireum</i> wrestler.

187
00:07:10,513 --> 00:07:13,224
So was my friend.
He was the Grand Champion.

188
00:07:13,308 --> 00:07:15,393
It's almost like you're him.

189
00:07:16,811 --> 00:07:18,438
- It is, yes.
- What?

190
00:07:18,521 --> 00:07:19,481
It's complicated.

191
00:07:19,564 --> 00:07:20,899
What's complicated?

192
00:07:20,982 --> 00:07:23,318
I was actually the host of <i>Star King</i>.

193
00:07:24,152 --> 00:07:27,155
HE HAS SOME SORT OF TIMELINE IN HIS HEAD
So, I'm Hocrates.

194
00:07:27,238 --> 00:07:31,242
- I'm the curious disciple of Socrates.
- Okay.

195
00:07:31,576 --> 00:07:34,621
I needed to gain a variety of experiences.

196
00:07:34,704 --> 00:07:37,207
So I did <i>ssireum</i>.

197
00:07:37,290 --> 00:07:38,375
Also, <i>The Knee-Drop Guru</i>.

198
00:07:38,458 --> 00:07:40,293
- Was that you?
- Yes!

199
00:07:41,002 --> 00:07:44,130
- Then--
- Then, aren't you Ho-dong?

200
00:07:44,798 --> 00:07:47,050
- That's the guy with the short hair.
- Yes.

201
00:07:48,343 --> 00:07:50,303
- It's complicated.
- I see.

202
00:07:50,387 --> 00:07:52,263
- I'll sort it out.
- I won't dig deep.

203
00:07:52,347 --> 00:07:53,890
- I won't pry.
- You can. Dig!

204
00:07:53,974 --> 00:07:55,767
DIDN'T EXPECT SOMEONE TO TAKE IT SERIOUSLY
Dig deeper!

205
00:07:55,850 --> 00:07:57,102
You even sound like him.

206
00:07:57,185 --> 00:07:59,437
- It's just a bit complicated.
- Okay.

207
00:07:59,646 --> 00:08:03,316
Talking about MMA
just brings me back, that's all.

208
00:08:03,400 --> 00:08:05,527
KIM DONG-HYUN'S FAVORITE BOOK
What's the book you're here to sell?

209
00:08:05,610 --> 00:08:08,029
I read this in my twenties.

210
00:08:08,113 --> 00:08:09,990
As you probably know,

211
00:08:10,073 --> 00:08:13,159
- I lived in the gym, covered in sweat.
- Right.

212
00:08:13,243 --> 00:08:15,036
I saw this book by chance one day.

213
00:08:15,412 --> 00:08:17,789
I haven't read that many books in my life.

214
00:08:17,872 --> 00:08:19,666
I can't read ones that are too thick.

215
00:08:19,749 --> 00:08:21,960
- It's a thin book with a big font.
- Yes.

216
00:08:22,043 --> 00:08:23,795
So I could finish it quickly.

217
00:08:23,878 --> 00:08:27,298
It gave me a lot of comfort at the time.

218
00:08:27,716 --> 00:08:29,426
It's not a fancy book,

219
00:08:29,509 --> 00:08:32,053
but I brought
<i>Don't Eat the Marshmallow Yet!</i>

220
00:08:32,387 --> 00:08:34,806
- I didn't even know it was popular.
- I see.

221
00:08:34,889 --> 00:08:37,434
SOLD OVER THREE MILLION COPIES
It's a bestseller.

222
00:08:37,517 --> 00:08:40,228
- I read it about 20 years ago.
- Right.

223
00:08:40,311 --> 00:08:41,938
Almost exactly 20 years ago.

224
00:08:42,022 --> 00:08:43,273
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

225
00:08:43,857 --> 00:08:45,066
KIM DONG-HYUN'S FAVORITE BOOK

226
00:08:45,150 --> 00:08:47,652
<i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>
BY JOACHIM DE POSADA, ELLEN SINGER

227
00:08:47,736 --> 00:08:50,488
A SELF-HELP BOOK THAT EXPLAINS
THE SECRET TO SUCCESS AND HAPPINESS

228
00:08:50,697 --> 00:08:54,701
THE 2005 FIRST EDITION IS WELL-KNOWN

229
00:08:54,784 --> 00:08:58,788
Could you explain to our viewers
what this book is about?

230
00:08:59,581 --> 00:09:02,751
When there are temptations
for immediate satisfaction,

231
00:09:02,834 --> 00:09:06,463
and you control and restrain yourself,

232
00:09:06,546 --> 00:09:08,923
you will get a bigger reward later on.

233
00:09:09,007 --> 00:09:10,717
- You can train that restraint.
- Right.

234
00:09:10,800 --> 00:09:12,052
It can be trained.

235
00:09:12,135 --> 00:09:14,679
When I read this book

236
00:09:14,763 --> 00:09:16,431
in my twenties,

237
00:09:17,390 --> 00:09:20,351
I was wondering
if I was doing the right thing

238
00:09:20,435 --> 00:09:22,479
by spending all my time training.

239
00:09:22,562 --> 00:09:24,522
Then, I saw the phrase in the book.

240
00:09:24,606 --> 00:09:26,316
- So--
- What phrase?

241
00:09:26,399 --> 00:09:28,943
I don't remember it exactly.

242
00:09:29,027 --> 00:09:30,862
But when I saw the book,

243
00:09:30,945 --> 00:09:32,489
I read that short phrase,

244
00:09:32,572 --> 00:09:34,991
and everything felt like
it was speaking to me.

245
00:09:35,075 --> 00:09:36,659
So what was the phrase?

246
00:09:36,743 --> 00:09:39,287
"Everyone wants to have fun

247
00:09:39,370 --> 00:09:42,832
and enjoy the youth that only comes once.

248
00:09:42,916 --> 00:09:45,085
But if you restrain yourself..."

249
00:09:45,168 --> 00:09:48,379
I'm paraphrasing this part
because I don't remember.

250
00:09:48,463 --> 00:09:52,300
"But if you restrain yourself
for the future,

251
00:09:52,842 --> 00:09:56,763
there will be
an awesome future waiting for you."

252
00:09:57,514 --> 00:10:00,016
It was something like that.
I forgot the rest.

253
00:10:00,100 --> 00:10:02,519
- That was the gist.
- You get it, right?

254
00:10:02,602 --> 00:10:04,896
You can find it again in the book.

255
00:10:05,522 --> 00:10:09,400
But it's a popular book,
so there are multiple editions.

256
00:10:09,484 --> 00:10:11,528
I can't find the edition that I read.

257
00:10:12,487 --> 00:10:15,698
The translations are all different.

258
00:10:15,782 --> 00:10:17,784
THERE ARE 20 EDITIONS ON COUPANG
So I got this one.

259
00:10:17,867 --> 00:10:20,954
- There are multiple translated versions.
- Oh, no.

260
00:10:21,037 --> 00:10:23,915
CURRENTLY PUBLISHED BY DEEP AND WIDE
More than one publisher printed it.

261
00:10:24,541 --> 00:10:29,754
YOU ONLY HAVE ONE YOUTH,
SO WHO WOULDN'T WANT TO ENJOY IT?

262
00:10:29,838 --> 00:10:32,757
BUT LIFE IS A MUCH LONGER JOURNEY
THAN YOU THINK

263
00:10:32,841 --> 00:10:35,718
PEOPLE WHO ENDURE
THROUGH THE MOST RADIANT TIME IN LIFE

264
00:10:35,802 --> 00:10:39,097
TO ACCOMPLISH GREATER THINGS
THAN JUST IMMEDIATE DESIRES

265
00:10:39,180 --> 00:10:42,267
WILL BE THE ONES WHO HAD
THE MOST SUCCESSFUL YOUTH OF THEM ALL

266
00:10:42,350 --> 00:10:44,978
FROM <i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>
2005 FIRST EDITION

267
00:10:45,603 --> 00:10:48,606
I was in my mid-twenties at the time.

268
00:10:48,690 --> 00:10:52,402
Most people in their twenties
want to enjoy it in a spectacular way.

269
00:10:52,485 --> 00:10:55,738
But I practically lived
in the gym at the time.

270
00:10:55,822 --> 00:10:57,240
I was doubtful
if it was the right way to live.

271
00:10:57,615 --> 00:11:01,369
But I realized
that I was doing the right thing.

272
00:11:01,452 --> 00:11:04,622
I became convinced that
I was having the most spectacular youth,

273
00:11:04,956 --> 00:11:08,084
devoting myself to something that I love.

274
00:11:08,168 --> 00:11:11,296
- There are so many temptations in life.
- Right.

275
00:11:11,379 --> 00:11:13,590
Choosing a bigger future reward over those

276
00:11:13,673 --> 00:11:15,383
takes restraint and control.

277
00:11:15,466 --> 00:11:17,844
- It takes self-control, right?
- Yes.

278
00:11:18,219 --> 00:11:20,305
- Speaking of the book,
- Yes.

279
00:11:20,388 --> 00:11:22,599
the marshmallow experiment is well-known.

280
00:11:22,682 --> 00:11:24,350
- The experiment, yes.
- Right?

281
00:11:24,434 --> 00:11:27,645
MARSHMALLOW GIVEN TO KIDS AGES 4 AND 5
You give kids 15 minutes.

282
00:11:27,729 --> 00:11:30,106
If they wait
and do not eat the marshmallow,

283
00:11:30,190 --> 00:11:31,941
- if they stay patient,
- Right.

284
00:11:32,025 --> 00:11:34,235
- they're promised two afterward.
- Right.

285
00:11:34,319 --> 00:11:35,820
- That's the experiment.
- Yes.

286
00:11:35,904 --> 00:11:37,113
THE KIDS WHO WAITED GREW UP
TO BE SUCCESSFUL IN LIFE

287
00:11:37,197 --> 00:11:41,618
EXPERIMENT LED BY WALTER MISCHEL
AT STANFORD UNIVERSITY IN 1970

288
00:11:41,701 --> 00:11:45,371
There are people who say
that this experiment is flawed.

289
00:11:45,455 --> 00:11:47,540
- Some people say that.
- That's right.

290
00:11:47,624 --> 00:11:48,875
These are the grounds.

291
00:11:48,958 --> 00:11:51,878
"The restraint it takes
not to take the marshmallow

292
00:11:51,961 --> 00:11:54,923
didn't take into account
the kids' environmental factors."

293
00:11:55,506 --> 00:11:58,801
Depending on each kid's background,

294
00:11:58,885 --> 00:12:02,347
if they've never had a marshmallow,
the 15 minutes will feel long.

295
00:12:02,430 --> 00:12:04,641
But for some kids,
a marshmallow is nothing special.

296
00:12:04,724 --> 00:12:06,893
- Right.
- So it's different for all of them.

297
00:12:06,976 --> 00:12:09,103
But stating that if you didn't take it,
you'll succeed,

298
00:12:09,187 --> 00:12:11,522
- Not at all.
- and if you did, you'll fail?

299
00:12:11,606 --> 00:12:12,899
- That's a good point.
- It's a stretch.

300
00:12:12,982 --> 00:12:14,692
- It's the wrong connection.
- Yes.

301
00:12:14,776 --> 00:12:16,319
That alone can't determine it.

302
00:12:16,402 --> 00:12:18,696
What if someone doesn't like marshmallows?

303
00:12:18,780 --> 00:12:21,241
- What if they're not a fan?
- Right.

304
00:12:21,324 --> 00:12:22,825
They won't want it anyway.

305
00:12:22,909 --> 00:12:24,702
You can't say they'll succeed for that.

306
00:12:24,786 --> 00:12:28,331
Maybe they prefer
gummies or candies over marshmallows.

307
00:12:28,414 --> 00:12:30,500
So, I don't think you can rely on

308
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:33,002
the outcome of that experiment.

309
00:12:33,086 --> 00:12:34,796
But the basic idea still stands.

310
00:12:34,879 --> 00:12:36,256
If there's something you want

311
00:12:36,339 --> 00:12:38,800
but you can restrain and control yourself,

312
00:12:38,883 --> 00:12:40,927
even with other things in life,

313
00:12:41,010 --> 00:12:43,513
you'll be able to endure the hardships.

314
00:12:43,596 --> 00:12:46,975
And that self-control can be trained, too.

315
00:12:47,058 --> 00:12:48,184
That seems valid.

316
00:12:48,268 --> 00:12:50,395
- But at the same time,
- Yes?

317
00:12:50,478 --> 00:12:52,480
if we restrain ourselves too much today

318
00:12:52,563 --> 00:12:54,482
for the happiness of tomorrow,

319
00:12:54,565 --> 00:12:57,360
wouldn't we miss out
on the happiness of today?

320
00:12:58,152 --> 00:12:59,779
It's something to think about.

321
00:12:59,862 --> 00:13:01,656
Because you like food, right?

322
00:13:01,739 --> 00:13:03,992
- I love food.
- They say the best food

323
00:13:04,075 --> 00:13:05,868
- is whatever's in season.
- Right.

324
00:13:05,952 --> 00:13:07,578
Why is seasonal food good?

325
00:13:08,788 --> 00:13:09,914
Because it's fresh?

326
00:13:11,416 --> 00:13:13,876
- Is that right?
- I wasn't quizzing you.

327
00:13:13,960 --> 00:13:15,336
Because you can only get it

328
00:13:15,420 --> 00:13:18,256
- when it's in season.
- Right.

329
00:13:18,339 --> 00:13:20,091
That's why it's good for you.

330
00:13:20,174 --> 00:13:23,136
- I think that's something to think about.
- That's true.

331
00:13:23,219 --> 00:13:25,096
If you just
restrain yourself for tomorrow,

332
00:13:25,179 --> 00:13:27,473
I'm worried you might end up

333
00:13:27,557 --> 00:13:30,768
missing out on the happiness of today.

334
00:13:30,852 --> 00:13:34,647
That's true. I think it's important
to keep the balance.

335
00:13:34,731 --> 00:13:36,024
The important thing

336
00:13:36,607 --> 00:13:38,026
- is balance.
- Balance.

337
00:13:38,109 --> 00:13:39,861
You can't be one or the other.

338
00:13:40,028 --> 00:13:42,405
Of course, you need balance.

339
00:13:42,947 --> 00:13:44,741
The warm-up went on a bit too long.

340
00:13:44,824 --> 00:13:46,701
- We got carried away with small talk.
- I see.

341
00:13:46,784 --> 00:13:48,619
Now, let's get into your life story.

342
00:13:48,703 --> 00:13:50,121
That was small talk?

343
00:13:52,415 --> 00:13:55,251
TIME FEELS DIFFERENT FOR A 2,000-YEAR-OLD
I thought we were wrapping up.

344
00:13:55,460 --> 00:13:57,503
That was small talk? I see.

345
00:13:57,962 --> 00:14:00,298
I already said everything I wanted to say.

346
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:02,759
That's everything I prepared.

347
00:14:02,842 --> 00:14:04,469
- You could ask...
- For athletes,

348
00:14:04,552 --> 00:14:06,095
that's important.

349
00:14:06,179 --> 00:14:07,764
- Yes.
- It's important.

350
00:14:07,847 --> 00:14:10,641
- For example, say there are five rounds
- Right.

351
00:14:10,725 --> 00:14:12,018
and three minutes in,

352
00:14:12,101 --> 00:14:14,145
you realize that you're out of energy.

353
00:14:14,228 --> 00:14:16,022
That happened to me in a match.

354
00:14:16,105 --> 00:14:17,523
I thought to myself,

355
00:14:17,607 --> 00:14:19,734
"Should I just lose this one?"

356
00:14:19,817 --> 00:14:21,069
THE BOOK IS ABOUT PATIENCE

357
00:14:21,152 --> 00:14:23,196
Too much time was left.

358
00:14:23,279 --> 00:14:26,699
I already did everything,
and used up all my energy.

359
00:14:26,783 --> 00:14:29,077
I was so tired.
I thought, "Should I lose?"

360
00:14:29,827 --> 00:14:32,121
"I'll win the next one."
I've experienced it.

361
00:14:32,205 --> 00:14:33,915
I was like, "Something's wrong."

362
00:14:34,457 --> 00:14:35,666
All right.

363
00:14:36,125 --> 00:14:37,877
- Just relax and have fun.
- I will.

364
00:14:37,960 --> 00:14:40,129
- That'll give you energy.
- Okay.

365
00:14:40,505 --> 00:14:43,966
Now, I'll ask you
some questions about your life.

366
00:14:44,050 --> 00:14:47,970
This is about the beginning
of Kim Dong-hyun as an MMA fighter.

367
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:50,306
In <i>Don't Eat the Marshmallow Yet</i>,

368
00:14:50,765 --> 00:14:53,810
it says, "Don't eat the marshmallow
in front of you right away."

369
00:14:53,893 --> 00:14:54,727
Right.

370
00:14:54,811 --> 00:14:58,314
"Wait until you can have
more marshmallows."

371
00:14:59,190 --> 00:15:00,691
Looking back on your career,

372
00:15:00,775 --> 00:15:04,237
there must have been several chances
for you to just eat your marshmallow.

373
00:15:04,320 --> 00:15:06,406
- We'll start at the very beginning.
- Okay.

374
00:15:06,906 --> 00:15:09,283
THE START OF HIS DREAM
When did you first decide

375
00:15:09,367 --> 00:15:11,285
to become an MMA fighter?

376
00:15:11,661 --> 00:15:14,580
Ever since I was a kid,

377
00:15:15,415 --> 00:15:17,125
I loved being active.

378
00:15:17,208 --> 00:15:19,585
I loved any kind of physical activity.

379
00:15:19,669 --> 00:15:22,422
There weren't many sports
you could choose from then.

380
00:15:22,505 --> 00:15:23,423
There are more now.

381
00:15:23,506 --> 00:15:27,176
But back then, I did taekwondo,
and a bit of judo as a kid.

382
00:15:27,260 --> 00:15:29,554
I watched the Olympic Games
and was in awe,

383
00:15:29,637 --> 00:15:32,515
so I decided to try judo.

384
00:15:33,724 --> 00:15:36,394
And when I was in school,

385
00:15:36,894 --> 00:15:39,105
I wanted to be strong.

386
00:15:39,188 --> 00:15:43,484
I was really into Hong Kong films,
martial arts, and being strong.

387
00:15:44,193 --> 00:15:46,446
I loved Jet Li and Stephen Chow films.

388
00:15:46,529 --> 00:15:48,322
- Right.
- In those films,

389
00:15:48,406 --> 00:15:51,534
I saw a lot of bad guys

390
00:15:51,617 --> 00:15:53,995
- harassing and robbing people.
- Right.

391
00:15:54,078 --> 00:15:55,705
So I wanted to be strong.

392
00:15:56,205 --> 00:15:59,292
Peace is only possible when you're strong.

393
00:15:59,375 --> 00:16:01,461
No one wants to mess with someone strong.

394
00:16:02,003 --> 00:16:04,255
- So--
- But judo makes you strong, too.

395
00:16:04,338 --> 00:16:06,466
Judo takes a lot of hard training.

396
00:16:06,549 --> 00:16:08,718
Here's what I mean by "strong."

397
00:16:09,844 --> 00:16:12,388
I was in a society called school, right?

398
00:16:12,472 --> 00:16:13,890
When I was doing judo,

399
00:16:13,973 --> 00:16:16,434
some of the big kids came to me

400
00:16:16,517 --> 00:16:19,103
and messed with me,
saying, "I heard you do judo."

401
00:16:19,187 --> 00:16:21,355
So, I realized

402
00:16:22,356 --> 00:16:25,401
that real strength means
that nobody touches you.

403
00:16:25,485 --> 00:16:26,861
That's what I was thinking.

404
00:16:26,944 --> 00:16:27,987
"So what do I do?

405
00:16:28,070 --> 00:16:29,489
To be strong at school,

406
00:16:29,572 --> 00:16:31,908
how many times do I have to fight?"

407
00:16:32,033 --> 00:16:33,701
That was my thought process.

408
00:16:33,784 --> 00:16:35,578
- I see.
- I went to school in Daejeon.

409
00:16:35,661 --> 00:16:37,038
I could fight in Daejeon,

410
00:16:37,121 --> 00:16:39,290
then Seoul, and then the whole country.

411
00:16:39,373 --> 00:16:42,335
But in the process, I'd get arrested.

412
00:16:42,418 --> 00:16:44,837
My parents would have to
beg for forgiveness.

413
00:16:44,921 --> 00:16:46,339
I'd already be in a bad place

414
00:16:46,422 --> 00:16:48,591
before I managed to prove my strength.

415
00:16:49,050 --> 00:16:50,218
That wouldn't do.

416
00:16:50,301 --> 00:16:53,471
I always run simulations in my mind.
I'm very imaginative.

417
00:16:53,554 --> 00:16:54,639
I wasn't sure I'd win.

418
00:16:54,722 --> 00:16:56,098
I knew I'd just quit

419
00:16:56,182 --> 00:16:57,934
after losing twice.

420
00:16:58,309 --> 00:17:00,603
A REAL TEAR-JERKER
That's not real strength.

421
00:17:00,686 --> 00:17:03,523
So I was thinking, "What should I do?"

422
00:17:03,606 --> 00:17:06,817
But at that time, as if by fate,

423
00:17:06,901 --> 00:17:08,736
- my house got cable.
- Okay.

424
00:17:08,819 --> 00:17:10,738
I don't know why. I think--

425
00:17:10,821 --> 00:17:12,573
- You didn't pay for it?
- No.

426
00:17:12,657 --> 00:17:14,700
Maybe because the neighbors got it.

427
00:17:14,784 --> 00:17:16,536
- Or--
- You still don't know?

428
00:17:16,619 --> 00:17:17,912
- I don't.
- How you got it?

429
00:17:17,995 --> 00:17:20,706
Out of nowhere,
we started getting foreign broadcasts.

430
00:17:20,790 --> 00:17:23,125
There was a Japanese MMA channel.

431
00:17:23,209 --> 00:17:24,627
It broadcasted MMA all day.

432
00:17:24,961 --> 00:17:27,421
So, I watched it.

433
00:17:27,505 --> 00:17:29,757
- All we knew were boxing gloves.
- Right.

434
00:17:29,840 --> 00:17:31,551
But they had open-finger ones

435
00:17:31,634 --> 00:17:33,594
with black pads on top.

436
00:17:33,678 --> 00:17:36,013
I was so shocked.
I was like, "What's this?"

437
00:17:36,097 --> 00:17:37,431
What was it called exactly?

438
00:17:37,515 --> 00:17:40,226
I didn't even know
what it was called at the time.

439
00:17:40,685 --> 00:17:43,396
But it did say <i>vale tudo</i>.

440
00:17:43,479 --> 00:17:44,605
<i>Tudo</i>, and not judo?

441
00:17:44,689 --> 00:17:47,400
So I thought
it was called <i>tudo</i>, but it wasn't.

442
00:17:47,483 --> 00:17:51,529
BRAZILIAN COMBAT SPORT, PRECURSOR TO MMA
I didn't even know it existed.

443
00:17:51,904 --> 00:17:53,739
Also, I thought it'd be like boxing,

444
00:17:53,823 --> 00:17:56,200
- but they started fighting on the ground.
- Right.

445
00:17:56,284 --> 00:17:59,662
I was like, "What is this?"
It just looked like a street fight.

446
00:17:59,745 --> 00:18:02,123
But there was a referee
and a winner at the end.

447
00:18:02,206 --> 00:18:03,207
For the winner,

448
00:18:03,291 --> 00:18:06,127
the crowd was cheering and going crazy.

449
00:18:06,210 --> 00:18:07,962
Saying they were the best.

450
00:18:09,297 --> 00:18:12,633
I was confused, but I was totally hooked.

451
00:18:12,717 --> 00:18:13,843
"This is it!"

452
00:18:13,926 --> 00:18:16,220
I wouldn't have to fight elsewhere.

453
00:18:16,304 --> 00:18:18,264
If I became good at that,

454
00:18:18,347 --> 00:18:20,433
- anyone would think I was strong.
- Right.

455
00:18:20,516 --> 00:18:22,476
Then, I found out about the UFC.

456
00:18:22,560 --> 00:18:24,145
Was there a UFC gym in Korea?

457
00:18:24,228 --> 00:18:26,272
There wasn't. So here's what I did.

458
00:18:26,647 --> 00:18:28,316
I trained at three gyms.

459
00:18:28,649 --> 00:18:31,819
After school, I went to do judo,
taekwondo, and hapkido.

460
00:18:31,902 --> 00:18:33,654
I went to all three of them.

461
00:18:33,738 --> 00:18:35,573
I trained in MMA in my own way.

462
00:18:35,656 --> 00:18:38,576
- You mixed three different combat sports,
- Yes.

463
00:18:38,659 --> 00:18:39,910
so it counts as MMA?

464
00:18:39,994 --> 00:18:41,203
"Mixed" Martial arts.

465
00:18:41,287 --> 00:18:42,913
MIX OF THREE MARTIAL ARTS
So, MMA.

466
00:18:42,997 --> 00:18:44,665
- So--
- That's very literal.

467
00:18:44,749 --> 00:18:47,001
It was my way
of training in MMA every day.

468
00:18:47,084 --> 00:18:50,129
- Right, you did judo, taekwondo,
- Yes.

469
00:18:50,212 --> 00:18:51,964
- and hapkido<i>.</i>
- That's MMA.

470
00:18:52,048 --> 00:18:53,633
- Mixed Martial Arts.
- Yes.

471
00:18:53,716 --> 00:18:55,134
- You learned to kick.
- Yes.

472
00:18:55,217 --> 00:18:58,763
Every day after school,
I'd come home and watch the fights.

473
00:18:58,846 --> 00:19:01,349
I wanted to keep replaying them
but I couldn't.

474
00:19:01,432 --> 00:19:02,558
So this is what I did.

475
00:19:02,975 --> 00:19:06,062
- I drew the techniques in my notebook,
- I see.

476
00:19:06,145 --> 00:19:08,314
and researched what the UFC was.

477
00:19:08,397 --> 00:19:10,316
I even found the UFC rules somewhere.

478
00:19:11,442 --> 00:19:12,943
- Do you have the notes?
- Yes.

479
00:19:13,027 --> 00:19:14,570
- I kept them.
- No way.

480
00:19:14,654 --> 00:19:15,780
Do you want to see them?

481
00:19:15,863 --> 00:19:16,864
Yes, I'd like that.

482
00:19:16,947 --> 00:19:18,991
I can sell you the notebook,
but it'll be expensive.

483
00:19:19,075 --> 00:19:20,201
HANDMADE BOOKS ARE
TOO EXPENSIVE FOR THE BOOKSHOP

484
00:19:20,284 --> 00:19:21,160
Is this the notebook?

485
00:19:21,243 --> 00:19:22,662
It's the notebook I used.

486
00:19:22,745 --> 00:19:24,038
Right. Thirty years ago, right?

487
00:19:25,039 --> 00:19:26,540
- That's right.
- Yes.

488
00:19:27,958 --> 00:19:29,460
Those are the UFC rules.

489
00:19:29,543 --> 00:19:31,128
- This is...
- I wrote it down in high school.

490
00:19:31,212 --> 00:19:32,296
The handwriting is bad.

491
00:19:32,380 --> 00:19:33,964
You wrote in English so well.

492
00:19:34,048 --> 00:19:35,049
It was in English.

493
00:19:35,132 --> 00:19:37,009
- I had to know what UFC stood for
- Right.

494
00:19:37,093 --> 00:19:38,219
since I was headed there.

495
00:19:38,302 --> 00:19:40,513
It was going to be my profession.

496
00:19:40,596 --> 00:19:41,847
- So...
- What's it short for?

497
00:19:42,390 --> 00:19:45,518
- Ultimate Fighting Championship.
- I see.

498
00:19:45,601 --> 00:19:46,811
I don't know what that means.

499
00:19:47,645 --> 00:19:48,813
- "Ultimate"
- I see.

500
00:19:48,896 --> 00:19:51,691
probably means something like "powerful."

501
00:19:52,400 --> 00:19:53,609
I'm sorry.

502
00:19:53,693 --> 00:19:55,277
ULTIMATE: FUNDAMENTAL, GREATEST

503
00:19:55,361 --> 00:19:58,948
So, poking the eyes is a foul.

504
00:19:59,740 --> 00:20:01,867
- You'd think there are no rules.
- Right.

505
00:20:01,951 --> 00:20:03,869
But when it comes to grabbing fingers,

506
00:20:03,953 --> 00:20:05,329
you can grab three.

507
00:20:05,413 --> 00:20:07,289
- But this is a foul.
- I see.

508
00:20:07,373 --> 00:20:08,874
You can't bend two fingers.

509
00:20:08,958 --> 00:20:10,251
- I see.
- Three is okay.

510
00:20:10,334 --> 00:20:12,044
The rules are very detailed.

511
00:20:12,128 --> 00:20:14,130
You found your path on your own.

512
00:20:14,630 --> 00:20:17,216
- Even with different techniques,
- That's crazy.

513
00:20:17,299 --> 00:20:19,093
I tried them on my mom.

514
00:20:19,176 --> 00:20:21,345
I'd ask her, "Mom, does this hurt?"

515
00:20:21,429 --> 00:20:23,264
My judo coach would get mad
if I did it in class.

516
00:20:23,347 --> 00:20:24,890
So whenever he was out,
I'd call the others over,

517
00:20:24,974 --> 00:20:28,185
and ask, "Does this hurt?
Try this one on me."

518
00:20:28,811 --> 00:20:29,979
All this when you were a student?

519
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:31,063
- Yes?
- Could you read this?

520
00:20:31,147 --> 00:20:32,857
What does that part say?

521
00:20:32,940 --> 00:20:37,737
This is something
I wrote back in high school.

522
00:20:38,487 --> 00:20:41,240
"Every man dreams of becoming
the best in the world.

523
00:20:41,824 --> 00:20:44,952
But they get beaten up by someone

524
00:20:45,035 --> 00:20:46,996
or get defeated,

525
00:20:47,413 --> 00:20:48,873
and they give up or change their dreams.

526
00:20:49,540 --> 00:20:51,751
And 99.9% of humans are like this.

527
00:20:51,834 --> 00:20:54,587
Only a small minority doesn't give up,

528
00:20:54,670 --> 00:20:57,173
tries hard,
and challenges themselves to achieve it."

529
00:20:57,673 --> 00:20:58,632
That's what I wrote.

530
00:20:58,924 --> 00:21:01,051
I really wanted to do MMA.

531
00:21:01,135 --> 00:21:03,721
But my father was not what you'd expect.

532
00:21:03,804 --> 00:21:06,515
He almost kind of coddled me.

533
00:21:06,599 --> 00:21:08,976
- Well, you are his precious son.
- He didn't...

534
00:21:09,059 --> 00:21:10,186
- He didn't even let me ride a bike.
- I see.

535
00:21:10,269 --> 00:21:11,437
- In case you hurt yourself.
- No.

536
00:21:11,520 --> 00:21:12,855
I was committed,

537
00:21:12,938 --> 00:21:15,608
but I knew my parents would say no,
so I wrote this.

538
00:21:16,400 --> 00:21:19,069
"When it comes to life goals,
be a bad son."

539
00:21:19,153 --> 00:21:20,654
I wrote that.

540
00:21:20,946 --> 00:21:22,072
If I listened to them--

541
00:21:22,156 --> 00:21:23,532
- As a student.
- Yes.

542
00:21:23,616 --> 00:21:26,869
For your life goals,
you had to be a bad son.

543
00:21:26,952 --> 00:21:28,746
"Live up to your parents' hopes

544
00:21:28,829 --> 00:21:30,956
and you'll only be part of their lives."

545
00:21:31,207 --> 00:21:33,626
I wouldn't want my son
to be like this, though.

546
00:21:34,084 --> 00:21:35,377
If my son were like this...

547
00:21:36,545 --> 00:21:38,297
If my son were like this...

548
00:21:38,422 --> 00:21:40,633
It's different when you're a parent.

549
00:21:40,716 --> 00:21:43,177
What if my son's like this?
That'd be a problem.

550
00:21:43,677 --> 00:21:45,638
THE TWO FATHERS ARE DEEP IN THOUGHT

551
00:21:45,721 --> 00:21:47,723
Anyway, I drew all these techniques.

552
00:21:47,807 --> 00:21:48,849
- Like this.
- That's amazing.

553
00:21:48,933 --> 00:21:51,060
This is before the armbar, right?

554
00:21:51,143 --> 00:21:53,187
- Yes, before the armbar.
- The position.

555
00:21:53,270 --> 00:21:56,106
I took down notes
and kept looking at the notebook.

556
00:21:56,941 --> 00:21:58,984
I also used comic books as a reference.

557
00:21:59,235 --> 00:22:01,570
- I just drew.
- Picturing it in your head?

558
00:22:02,029 --> 00:22:05,950
DRAWINGS HE MADE
DREAMING OF BECOMING A FIGHTER

559
00:22:06,575 --> 00:22:10,037
YOUNG DONG-HYUN'S DREAMS GREW AS HE DREW

560
00:22:10,704 --> 00:22:14,667
THESE NOTES BECAME A TREASURE TO HIM
AFTER 30 YEARS

561
00:22:14,750 --> 00:22:16,502
- You were picturing the moves.
- Right.

562
00:22:16,585 --> 00:22:19,463
You must've been so sleepy at night.

563
00:22:19,547 --> 00:22:22,007
You gave up sleep, endured the pain,

564
00:22:22,091 --> 00:22:23,884
and visualized to achieve your dream.

565
00:22:23,968 --> 00:22:25,511
IF YOU FIGHT SLEEP,
YOU CAN ACHIEVE YOUR DREAM

566
00:22:25,594 --> 00:22:28,764
Yes, but I was never tired.

567
00:22:28,848 --> 00:22:31,225
I was so into this world

568
00:22:31,308 --> 00:22:32,810
- and excited.
- I see.

569
00:22:32,893 --> 00:22:36,605
I was just so lost
and happy in that world.

570
00:22:40,359 --> 00:22:42,194
What I'm grateful for

571
00:22:42,486 --> 00:22:45,072
is that I found something
that I really love.

572
00:22:45,155 --> 00:22:48,117
I hope other people can find that too.

573
00:22:50,077 --> 00:22:51,704
If we look back, in a way,

574
00:22:51,787 --> 00:22:55,082
in the world of Korean MMA,

575
00:22:55,165 --> 00:22:56,333
you're a trailblazer.

576
00:22:56,417 --> 00:22:58,252
Was there a competition in South Korea?

577
00:22:58,335 --> 00:22:59,420
In South Korea?

578
00:22:59,503 --> 00:23:01,755
My plan was to go to Japan.

579
00:23:01,839 --> 00:23:03,215
I wanted to be a champion,

580
00:23:03,299 --> 00:23:06,260
and I was confident I could beat everyone.

581
00:23:06,343 --> 00:23:07,636
After military service,

582
00:23:07,720 --> 00:23:10,097
I was going to head to Japan to be a pro.

583
00:23:10,180 --> 00:23:11,765
But there was a new one here.

584
00:23:11,849 --> 00:23:13,517
It was a competition called KPW.

585
00:23:13,726 --> 00:23:15,227
It was 50,000 won to enter.

586
00:23:15,311 --> 00:23:17,563
It was a one-day tournament

587
00:23:17,646 --> 00:23:19,189
with a winner at the end.

588
00:23:19,273 --> 00:23:21,025
I fought three people.

589
00:23:21,108 --> 00:23:22,693
- I won easily.
- It was your debut match?

590
00:23:22,776 --> 00:23:23,694
- Yes.
- I see.

591
00:23:23,777 --> 00:23:25,696
Also, an amateur jiujitsu competition...

592
00:23:25,779 --> 00:23:27,740
It was the first jiujitsu competition
in the country.

593
00:23:27,823 --> 00:23:29,283
I won that, too.

594
00:23:29,366 --> 00:23:32,036
Winning becomes a habit like that.

595
00:23:32,453 --> 00:23:33,621
- It felt good.
- Right.

596
00:23:33,704 --> 00:23:35,915
- "I'm finally here."
- You learn how to win.

597
00:23:35,998 --> 00:23:37,499
I remember being so excited.

598
00:23:37,583 --> 00:23:39,668
- You were doing so well.
- Yes.

599
00:23:39,752 --> 00:23:41,587
But you quit all of a sudden.

600
00:23:41,670 --> 00:23:44,214
Yes, I loved and enjoyed it,

601
00:23:44,715 --> 00:23:47,593
but I was thinking
about the future of MMA.

602
00:23:48,510 --> 00:23:52,222
I thought it was just a trend
that would go away soon.

603
00:23:52,306 --> 00:23:53,557
- At the time.
- I get it.

604
00:23:53,641 --> 00:23:55,643
What was the fight purse like?

605
00:23:55,726 --> 00:23:56,852
The fight purse

606
00:23:57,519 --> 00:23:59,021
was almost non-existent.

607
00:23:59,104 --> 00:24:00,439
I had to pay to enter.

608
00:24:00,522 --> 00:24:03,108
It was 300,000 to 500,000 won.

609
00:24:03,901 --> 00:24:05,277
I wanted

610
00:24:05,361 --> 00:24:06,487
to make a lot of money

611
00:24:06,570 --> 00:24:08,781
and try other things.

612
00:24:08,864 --> 00:24:12,409
I read that you did
a lot of hard labor after quitting.

613
00:24:12,493 --> 00:24:13,661
- I wanted to make money.
- Right.

614
00:24:13,744 --> 00:24:15,788
I did a lot of different work for a year.

615
00:24:15,871 --> 00:24:19,249
That was around 2005.

616
00:24:19,333 --> 00:24:22,711
I was interested in architecture
and wanted to learn.

617
00:24:22,795 --> 00:24:25,214
I wanted to get a degree and work.

618
00:24:25,923 --> 00:24:27,800
But it was harder than I thought.

619
00:24:27,883 --> 00:24:29,259
It requires a lot of studying.

620
00:24:29,343 --> 00:24:32,096
Unlike MMA, it wasn't something you loved.

621
00:24:32,179 --> 00:24:33,639
So the process must've felt hard.

622
00:24:33,722 --> 00:24:36,350
When I wrote techniques,
I enjoyed every minute of it.

623
00:24:36,433 --> 00:24:39,103
- But with this, it was driving me crazy.
- I see.

624
00:24:39,186 --> 00:24:40,729
I had to just sit and study.

625
00:24:41,438 --> 00:24:43,023
I thought I was going insane.

626
00:24:43,107 --> 00:24:45,776
- So I gave that up.
- I see.

627
00:24:46,276 --> 00:24:48,445
Instead, I decided to just work on site.

628
00:24:48,529 --> 00:24:50,864
I saw "building facilities engineer"

629
00:24:50,948 --> 00:24:53,158
in a want ad and went there.

630
00:24:53,242 --> 00:24:54,994
But it wasn't quite that.

631
00:24:55,077 --> 00:24:57,037
The job was to unclog drains.

632
00:24:57,204 --> 00:24:58,747
It was near Sinsa station.

633
00:24:58,831 --> 00:24:59,707
I still remember.

634
00:24:59,790 --> 00:25:02,501
We were sitting
in an old-school coffee shop in Sinsa.

635
00:25:02,584 --> 00:25:05,045
The boss said, "You're young.
Can you handle it?"

636
00:25:05,129 --> 00:25:07,381
I was like
"Isn't this job for young people?"

637
00:25:07,464 --> 00:25:10,134
So I said, "Of course!" and took the job.

638
00:25:10,217 --> 00:25:11,844
He gave me a lot of hope.

639
00:25:11,927 --> 00:25:14,805
He said, "A lot of young people
don't do this because it's hard.

640
00:25:14,888 --> 00:25:17,016
But if you endure and make it your own,

641
00:25:17,099 --> 00:25:19,143
you'll make a lot of money."

642
00:25:19,226 --> 00:25:20,644
I told him I was confident

643
00:25:21,020 --> 00:25:22,896
and that I liked anything physical.

644
00:25:22,980 --> 00:25:25,941
The job was to unclog restaurant drains.

645
00:25:26,025 --> 00:25:30,070
I unclogged a lot of toilets
and restaurants in Gangnam.

646
00:25:30,154 --> 00:25:32,364
I even unclogged the drain
at the Shilla Hotel.

647
00:25:32,448 --> 00:25:34,992
- When it was clogged?
- Yes.

648
00:25:35,075 --> 00:25:36,243
I'd go in the back

649
00:25:36,326 --> 00:25:38,287
to unclog it from the outside.

650
00:25:38,370 --> 00:25:40,789
When it unclogs, everything bursts out.

651
00:25:40,914 --> 00:25:43,167
- That was my job.
- Did it get all over?

652
00:25:43,250 --> 00:25:44,668
- Yes.
- Feces?

653
00:25:44,752 --> 00:25:46,462
It wasn't feces.

654
00:25:46,837 --> 00:25:48,297
- It was generally food waste.
- I see.

655
00:25:48,380 --> 00:25:49,673
Sometimes, it bursts out.

656
00:25:49,757 --> 00:25:51,383
But it's pretty satisfying
when it unclogs.

657
00:25:52,259 --> 00:25:54,595
Seriously, it's satisfying
when it unclogs.

658
00:25:54,678 --> 00:25:55,512
I can tell you why.

659
00:25:55,596 --> 00:25:57,097
Once it unclogs, I go home.

660
00:25:57,181 --> 00:25:58,849
I couldn't go home if it didn't.

661
00:25:59,433 --> 00:26:01,685
I'd think, "Come on, why won't it unclog?"

662
00:26:01,769 --> 00:26:03,228
It didn't even feel dirty.

663
00:26:03,312 --> 00:26:04,480
When it unclogged,

664
00:26:04,563 --> 00:26:06,523
I'd be like, "I'm going home!"

665
00:26:07,232 --> 00:26:08,233
I mean it.

666
00:26:08,567 --> 00:26:11,028
I still remember that.

667
00:26:11,111 --> 00:26:11,987
I feel you.

668
00:26:12,071 --> 00:26:14,948
It's a hard job.
It keeps almost unclogging,

669
00:26:15,032 --> 00:26:17,242
- and when it does, it's satisfying.
- Right.

670
00:26:17,326 --> 00:26:18,619
- It is.
- Right?

671
00:26:18,702 --> 00:26:19,787
You have no idea.

672
00:26:19,870 --> 00:26:22,790
Just hearing about it is satisfying.

673
00:26:22,873 --> 00:26:24,249
- So satisfying.
- When it passes through,

674
00:26:24,333 --> 00:26:26,168
it's very satisfying.

675
00:26:26,251 --> 00:26:29,963
But I worked that job
for less than two months.

676
00:26:30,047 --> 00:26:33,175
I also quit my job at the Internet café
after three days.

677
00:26:33,801 --> 00:26:35,677
Working at an Internet café is no joke.

678
00:26:35,969 --> 00:26:37,596
It's harder than most restaurants.

679
00:26:39,139 --> 00:26:40,390
Customers keep calling you.

680
00:26:40,474 --> 00:26:42,935
You know how you can
order food from your seat?

681
00:26:43,018 --> 00:26:44,978
Restaurants have 20 tables, max.

682
00:26:45,062 --> 00:26:46,730
It's a restaurant with 100 tables.

683
00:26:47,564 --> 00:26:49,149
You have to serve all of them.

684
00:26:49,233 --> 00:26:50,901
You cook food for them

685
00:26:50,984 --> 00:26:52,778
and clean up after they leave.

686
00:26:52,861 --> 00:26:54,655
They order noodles and side dishes
and so on.

687
00:26:54,738 --> 00:26:56,532
The bells don't stop ringing.

688
00:26:56,615 --> 00:26:57,574
It was so hard.

689
00:26:57,658 --> 00:26:59,952
The boss there said the same thing.

690
00:27:00,035 --> 00:27:01,453
"This is not an easy job,

691
00:27:01,912 --> 00:27:04,164
but if you endure and run the business..."

692
00:27:04,248 --> 00:27:05,874
That's why I hate hearing that.

693
00:27:05,958 --> 00:27:08,627
It's one of the things
I hate to hear the most.

694
00:27:09,211 --> 00:27:10,379
So I quit after three days.

695
00:27:10,754 --> 00:27:11,922
I didn't even get paid.

696
00:27:12,005 --> 00:27:13,257
And there were more.

697
00:27:13,674 --> 00:27:16,844
So my family made fun of me every holiday.

698
00:27:16,927 --> 00:27:19,888
"You give up too easily."
I got that a lot.

699
00:27:19,972 --> 00:27:22,558
But when it came to training,

700
00:27:22,641 --> 00:27:25,727
I never missed a day, rain or shine.

701
00:27:25,811 --> 00:27:27,980
- It was something you loved. That's why.
- Yes.

702
00:27:28,063 --> 00:27:29,439
- Yes.
- You can't

703
00:27:29,523 --> 00:27:31,400
just endure everything.

704
00:27:31,483 --> 00:27:33,485
- It should be for what you love.
- Right.

705
00:27:33,569 --> 00:27:35,696
When you endure through your youth,

706
00:27:35,779 --> 00:27:37,239
there will be a reward.

707
00:27:37,322 --> 00:27:38,740
But I quit without hesitation.

708
00:27:39,366 --> 00:27:41,160
Can I do this forever?

709
00:27:41,243 --> 00:27:43,036
Am I really happy doing this?

710
00:27:43,287 --> 00:27:44,621
Can I bet my life on this?

711
00:27:44,705 --> 00:27:46,832
It's important to be able to judge that.

712
00:27:46,915 --> 00:27:50,252
You should have the courage to quit
when it's not for you.

713
00:27:50,335 --> 00:27:53,964
That's also something I want to emphasize.

714
00:27:54,047 --> 00:27:55,382
That also takes courage.

715
00:27:57,301 --> 00:27:59,553
YOU FEEL MORE AT EASE

716
00:27:59,636 --> 00:28:02,514
WHEN YOU HAVE A GOAL
AND FOCUS ON WHAT YOU HAVE TO DO

717
00:28:02,598 --> 00:28:04,558
YOU BECOME A STABLE PERSON

718
00:28:04,641 --> 00:28:06,977
FROM <i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>

719
00:28:07,060 --> 00:28:10,397
In the book, when Charlie is facing
a new challenge,

720
00:28:10,480 --> 00:28:12,858
he puts this down
as something he should do.

721
00:28:12,941 --> 00:28:16,028
"I put all of my faith in myself,
who is pursuing success."

722
00:28:16,445 --> 00:28:17,571
That's what he writes.

723
00:28:18,488 --> 00:28:20,407
Not putting all his faith in success,

724
00:28:20,490 --> 00:28:22,659
but believing in himself,
who is pursuing it.

725
00:28:24,453 --> 00:28:25,579
Did I say that?

726
00:28:26,246 --> 00:28:28,540
- It's in the book.
- Charlie said that. Sorry.

727
00:28:28,957 --> 00:28:30,667
- I mentioned his name.
- Did you?

728
00:28:30,751 --> 00:28:32,836
- Yes.
- I don't remember saying that.

729
00:28:32,920 --> 00:28:34,630
- You never did.
- I see.

730
00:28:34,713 --> 00:28:35,839
- No.
- I'm sorry.

731
00:28:35,923 --> 00:28:39,051
You can only experience
success or failure after you try.

732
00:28:39,134 --> 00:28:40,928
What do you get when you succeed?

733
00:28:41,553 --> 00:28:43,263
- A sense of achievement.
- Right.

734
00:28:43,347 --> 00:28:44,473
- A big one.
- Right.

735
00:28:44,556 --> 00:28:45,974
What if you fail?

736
00:28:46,975 --> 00:28:49,436
When you fail, you learn so much.

737
00:28:49,519 --> 00:28:50,604
- You learn something.
- Yes.

738
00:28:50,687 --> 00:28:51,772
- So--
- That's so nice.

739
00:28:51,855 --> 00:28:54,608
There's a saying in MMA.
"You win or you learn."

740
00:28:54,900 --> 00:28:56,860
You don't lose. You either win or learn.

741
00:28:57,319 --> 00:28:58,737
A lot of fighters say this.

742
00:28:58,820 --> 00:29:01,657
"Who has ever retired
without losing at least once?

743
00:29:01,740 --> 00:29:02,950
Everybody loses.

744
00:29:03,033 --> 00:29:05,327
You only see who someone really is
when they lose."

745
00:29:05,410 --> 00:29:07,037
People also say that.

746
00:29:07,120 --> 00:29:10,499
When I was a pro,

747
00:29:10,582 --> 00:29:13,835
losing or failing

748
00:29:13,919 --> 00:29:15,629
made me think deeper and learn.

749
00:29:17,839 --> 00:29:20,175
"I was short on this and that.

750
00:29:20,259 --> 00:29:21,260
I should do this."

751
00:29:21,760 --> 00:29:24,513
And what I always realized in the end

752
00:29:24,596 --> 00:29:26,431
was that I failed

753
00:29:26,515 --> 00:29:28,350
because I didn't try hard enough.

754
00:29:29,309 --> 00:29:30,727
That was the conclusion.

755
00:29:30,811 --> 00:29:33,272
That made me work harder.

756
00:29:33,730 --> 00:29:36,358
When you're about to try something,

757
00:29:36,441 --> 00:29:38,110
you need courage,

758
00:29:38,193 --> 00:29:40,237
and what stops you is fear.

759
00:29:40,320 --> 00:29:41,280
That's right.

760
00:29:41,363 --> 00:29:44,199
You're scared you'd fail terribly.

761
00:29:44,283 --> 00:29:45,784
Fear is a strange thing.

762
00:29:45,867 --> 00:29:48,620
Since high school, I drew in my notebooks,

763
00:29:48,704 --> 00:29:51,248
and I was so into that world.

764
00:29:51,331 --> 00:29:53,625
But when I entered competitions,

765
00:29:53,709 --> 00:29:57,045
I'd sometimes think,
"Why did I decide to do this?

766
00:29:57,629 --> 00:29:59,673
I have to go through this anxiety

767
00:29:59,756 --> 00:30:00,966
- and fear,
- Right.

768
00:30:02,092 --> 00:30:05,470
and for what? What's the point?

769
00:30:05,554 --> 00:30:07,723
Why do I have to go through all of this?"

770
00:30:07,806 --> 00:30:10,684
This fear popped up in my head
from time to time.

771
00:30:10,767 --> 00:30:12,019
Some aspiring fighters

772
00:30:12,102 --> 00:30:14,438
come to me sometimes and tell me.

773
00:30:15,314 --> 00:30:18,066
"I've been sleepless and scared for days.

774
00:30:18,150 --> 00:30:19,609
Maybe this isn't my path.

775
00:30:20,068 --> 00:30:21,862
Maybe I'm not built for MMA."

776
00:30:21,945 --> 00:30:24,489
- Right.
- They voice their concerns.

777
00:30:24,906 --> 00:30:28,827
But any fighter who really wants to win
goes through the same.

778
00:30:29,369 --> 00:30:32,247
All of the biggest fighters we know,

779
00:30:32,331 --> 00:30:33,874
- I've seen them in waiting rooms.
- Right.

780
00:30:33,957 --> 00:30:35,834
They all get super nervous.

781
00:30:35,917 --> 00:30:37,461
But the moment they step out,

782
00:30:37,544 --> 00:30:39,588
- they put on a performance.
- Right.

783
00:30:39,671 --> 00:30:41,882
- But that's--
- They strut like this.

784
00:30:41,965 --> 00:30:43,550
- Right.
- Not like in the green room.

785
00:30:43,633 --> 00:30:46,261
- Of course.
- I don't think that's fear.

786
00:30:46,345 --> 00:30:49,389
They're nervous because they want to win.

787
00:30:49,473 --> 00:30:50,891
They're not scared.

788
00:30:50,974 --> 00:30:52,601
They want their effort to show.

789
00:30:52,684 --> 00:30:55,771
When you're focused on that,
you can get nervous.

790
00:30:55,854 --> 00:30:58,482
I think it's important
to control that nervousness.

791
00:30:59,191 --> 00:31:02,152
WHETHER YOU'RE A LION OR A GAZELLE
YOU MUST RUN AT SUNRISE

792
00:31:02,235 --> 00:31:04,029
FROM <i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>

793
00:31:04,112 --> 00:31:06,073
You have three nicknames.

794
00:31:06,531 --> 00:31:07,824
"Nogueira" Kim Dong-hyun,

795
00:31:08,492 --> 00:31:09,993
"Stun Gun" Kim Dong-hyun,

796
00:31:10,077 --> 00:31:11,620
- and "Cicada Kim."
- Right.

797
00:31:11,703 --> 00:31:13,997
Could you explain those nicknames for us?

798
00:31:14,081 --> 00:31:17,834
When I first started fighting
a long time ago,

799
00:31:17,918 --> 00:31:19,753
a fighter named Antônio Nogueira

800
00:31:19,836 --> 00:31:22,422
- was good at jiujitsu and grappling.
- Right.

801
00:31:22,506 --> 00:31:26,426
I liked to be on the ground
using jiujitsu moves like him.

802
00:31:26,510 --> 00:31:27,886
- When it comes to nicknames,
- Yes?

803
00:31:27,969 --> 00:31:29,888
for example, there's a Korean fighter

804
00:31:29,971 --> 00:31:31,264
called "Korean Tyson."

805
00:31:31,348 --> 00:31:34,059
He kind of looks like Tyson,

806
00:31:34,142 --> 00:31:36,728
so he has
a cool English nickname like that.

807
00:31:36,812 --> 00:31:38,814
At the time, a reporter called me,

808
00:31:38,980 --> 00:31:40,774
not "Korean Nogueira,"

809
00:31:40,857 --> 00:31:43,068
but "Domestic Nogueira."

810
00:31:43,151 --> 00:31:44,903
That's what the article said.

811
00:31:44,986 --> 00:31:47,406
I mean, they could've said
"Korean Nogueira."

812
00:31:47,489 --> 00:31:50,200
KOREAN TYSON, KO SEOK-HYEON
Maybe they hated me.

813
00:31:50,283 --> 00:31:53,453
DOMESTIC NOGUEIRA
But I think people found that funny.

814
00:31:53,537 --> 00:31:55,580
My nickname was "Domestic Nogueira."

815
00:31:55,664 --> 00:31:58,625
- And then there's "Stun Gun."
- Right.

816
00:31:58,708 --> 00:32:00,043
After I won by KO,

817
00:32:00,127 --> 00:32:02,421
it was like my opponent
was out by a stun gun.

818
00:32:02,504 --> 00:32:03,755
When I was in Japan,

819
00:32:03,839 --> 00:32:05,257
I always won by KO.

820
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:09,010
All of my opponents passed out.

821
00:32:09,136 --> 00:32:13,181
Since "Domestic Nogueira"
was not a very cool nickname,

822
00:32:13,265 --> 00:32:15,934
a fan gave me a new one on Cyworld.

823
00:32:16,393 --> 00:32:17,894
That was "Stun Gun."

824
00:32:17,978 --> 00:32:19,396
I really liked it,

825
00:32:19,479 --> 00:32:20,647
so I made it my ring name.

826
00:32:21,106 --> 00:32:22,858
I was going by that,

827
00:32:22,941 --> 00:32:25,068
but in the UFC,
I was less like a stun gun.

828
00:32:25,652 --> 00:32:28,405
- I kept hanging off my opponent's back.
- I see.

829
00:32:28,488 --> 00:32:30,490
Weirdly, the UFC fighters

830
00:32:30,574 --> 00:32:32,993
kept giving me their backs
and couldn't escape my grasp.

831
00:32:33,076 --> 00:32:34,995
Since it made me win,
I went with that strategy.

832
00:32:35,078 --> 00:32:36,872
- You hung off their backs.
- Yes.

833
00:32:36,955 --> 00:32:38,498
They couldn't shake me off.

834
00:32:38,999 --> 00:32:42,002
So, a Korean fan saw that,

835
00:32:42,669 --> 00:32:44,671
and thought my play was boring

836
00:32:44,754 --> 00:32:46,798
and not fun,

837
00:32:46,882 --> 00:32:49,509
and said I looked like
a cicada on an old tree.

838
00:32:49,593 --> 00:32:51,219
That's what they said.

839
00:32:52,596 --> 00:32:55,182
- It's not like anyone can do that.
- It's hard.

840
00:32:55,265 --> 00:32:58,310
It's not easy to bind your opponent
by hanging off their back.

841
00:32:58,393 --> 00:33:00,187
- It's a difficult technique.
- Right.

842
00:33:00,270 --> 00:33:01,938
It's an incredible technique.

843
00:33:02,105 --> 00:33:04,858
I've trained for many hours
to get on my opponent's back.

844
00:33:04,941 --> 00:33:06,693
In the UFC,

845
00:33:06,776 --> 00:33:09,279
I controlled opponents
longer than most fighters.

846
00:33:09,362 --> 00:33:11,823
You must've been sad
the fans didn't see it.

847
00:33:12,491 --> 00:33:13,325
I was very sad.

848
00:33:14,159 --> 00:33:14,993
Of course I was.

849
00:33:15,619 --> 00:33:17,120
This is harder than you think!

850
00:33:17,204 --> 00:33:18,705
Outside of Korea,

851
00:33:18,788 --> 00:33:21,291
they said I was a bit boring to watch,

852
00:33:21,875 --> 00:33:22,792
but I was strong.

853
00:33:22,876 --> 00:33:24,961
They all knew I could mess them up.

854
00:33:25,045 --> 00:33:27,756
But in Korea, all they thought

855
00:33:28,215 --> 00:33:29,508
was that my matches were boring.

856
00:33:30,717 --> 00:33:32,761
Even when I won, they were hating on me.

857
00:33:33,261 --> 00:33:35,013
Only my team was happy.

858
00:33:35,096 --> 00:33:37,057
We'd be celebrating in the hotel room.

859
00:33:37,140 --> 00:33:38,391
I stayed off the Internet.

860
00:33:38,475 --> 00:33:40,310
People were saying in the comments

861
00:33:40,393 --> 00:33:43,730
that when I was on,
it was time to go for a smoke.

862
00:33:44,314 --> 00:33:47,025
You could smoke, eat, and come back
and I'd be the same.

863
00:33:47,192 --> 00:33:49,653
Even if you went out and came back,
I'd be in the same position.

864
00:33:49,736 --> 00:33:51,154
That's what they said.

865
00:33:51,238 --> 00:33:53,490
I was in the UFC,
but my matches were boring.

866
00:33:53,573 --> 00:33:55,283
That's a bit harsh.

867
00:33:55,367 --> 00:33:57,452
I wanted to be dynamic,

868
00:33:57,536 --> 00:33:59,079
- I see.
- but once I latched on,

869
00:33:59,162 --> 00:34:01,831
I'd think it was still better to win.

870
00:34:01,915 --> 00:34:03,917
If you're good at something,

871
00:34:04,000 --> 00:34:05,502
- Right. Exactly.
- you stick with it.

872
00:34:05,585 --> 00:34:07,254
I mean, those are the rules.

873
00:34:07,337 --> 00:34:09,714
Blame the person who can't get out,
not the person holding on.

874
00:34:09,798 --> 00:34:12,259
They should've trained more
so they could get out.

875
00:34:12,968 --> 00:34:15,095
But it's true, my matches were boring.

876
00:34:15,178 --> 00:34:16,596
Even I don't watch my matches.

877
00:34:16,680 --> 00:34:18,348
Even I don't watch them.

878
00:34:18,431 --> 00:34:20,225
I watch the more dynamic fights.

879
00:34:20,308 --> 00:34:23,937
You fought with a lot of special fighters.

880
00:34:24,020 --> 00:34:26,273
- Carlos Condit.
- Yes.

881
00:34:26,356 --> 00:34:28,149
FIFTH WEC WELTERWEIGHT CHAMPION

882
00:34:28,233 --> 00:34:30,193
THREE WELTERWEIGHT TITLE DEFENSES

883
00:34:30,277 --> 00:34:32,529
SECOND UFC INTERIM WELTERWEIGHT CHAMPION

884
00:34:32,612 --> 00:34:35,031
So, I was winning in the UFC.

885
00:34:35,115 --> 00:34:37,117
- I kept winning by decision.
- Right.

886
00:34:37,200 --> 00:34:39,202
I just wanted to keep winning.

887
00:34:39,286 --> 00:34:40,870
There's no need to take risks.

888
00:34:40,954 --> 00:34:43,665
So, I won many times
by just hanging onto opponents.

889
00:34:43,748 --> 00:34:45,667
I won five times in a row.

890
00:34:45,750 --> 00:34:48,336
So they were like, "Yes, he's strong,

891
00:34:48,420 --> 00:34:51,256
but someone should do something."
That was the vibe.

892
00:34:51,339 --> 00:34:54,801
THEY WANTED TO END THE BORING STREAK
So they brought in a strong opponent.

893
00:34:54,884 --> 00:34:56,970
He was a very strong fighter.

894
00:34:57,053 --> 00:34:58,680
I heard that if he won that one,

895
00:34:58,972 --> 00:35:01,266
he'd be close to the championship fight.

896
00:35:01,349 --> 00:35:03,351
What I thought at the time was,

897
00:35:03,435 --> 00:35:05,020
not "Finally, it's my time."

898
00:35:05,103 --> 00:35:07,022
It was, "I'm not there yet, so why me?"

899
00:35:07,105 --> 00:35:09,107
I didn't think highly of myself.

900
00:35:09,190 --> 00:35:10,358
"I'm fighting him?"

901
00:35:10,442 --> 00:35:13,445
In the interview, I said I'd try my best
to win the championship.

902
00:35:13,528 --> 00:35:16,990
But I was surprised that I kept winning.

903
00:35:17,073 --> 00:35:18,366
- I'm...
- After five times?

904
00:35:18,450 --> 00:35:19,701
Yes. "I'm not good enough.

905
00:35:19,784 --> 00:35:21,202
Are they going easy on me?"

906
00:35:23,246 --> 00:35:26,583
So, I fought Carlos Condit.

907
00:35:26,666 --> 00:35:28,001
He's very skilled.

908
00:35:28,084 --> 00:35:29,669
I was about to tackle him,

909
00:35:30,629 --> 00:35:32,005
and then it was over.

910
00:35:32,422 --> 00:35:34,007
I lost for the first time ever.

911
00:35:34,674 --> 00:35:37,427
It was the same as depicted
in comic books and movies.

912
00:35:38,261 --> 00:35:39,846
I was blinking slowly.

913
00:35:39,929 --> 00:35:42,182
My eyes were blinking like this.

914
00:35:43,183 --> 00:35:45,060
It was silent. I didn't hear a thing.

915
00:35:45,685 --> 00:35:47,270
First, I started to see.

916
00:35:49,439 --> 00:35:51,066
He was jumping around.

917
00:35:51,149 --> 00:35:52,400
- He was.
- The opponent?

918
00:35:52,484 --> 00:35:53,568
He was jumping around.

919
00:35:53,652 --> 00:35:54,903
- You didn't know why?
- And...

920
00:35:54,986 --> 00:35:57,030
And people stepped into the ring.

921
00:35:57,739 --> 00:35:59,658
"What? Where am I?"

922
00:35:59,741 --> 00:36:01,785
I suddenly could hear again.

923
00:36:02,452 --> 00:36:04,621
I heard the crowd cheering loudly.

924
00:36:06,247 --> 00:36:07,457
"What's going on?"

925
00:36:08,166 --> 00:36:10,377
I tried to understand what was happening.

926
00:36:10,794 --> 00:36:12,754
I didn't realize I'd just fought.

927
00:36:12,837 --> 00:36:13,922
I didn't at that moment.

928
00:36:14,005 --> 00:36:15,799
I didn't think
it was the day of the match.

929
00:36:16,132 --> 00:36:17,676
I just thought, "Why am I here?

930
00:36:18,510 --> 00:36:19,844
Did I just wake up?

931
00:36:19,928 --> 00:36:21,930
Where am I? Is it the morning?"

932
00:36:22,013 --> 00:36:23,098
I'm serious.

933
00:36:23,181 --> 00:36:25,767
I can't forget that moment in my life.

934
00:36:25,850 --> 00:36:27,352
I remember it clearly.

935
00:36:27,435 --> 00:36:28,770
"Hold on.

936
00:36:29,062 --> 00:36:30,855
Right, I'm in the US." I realized that.

937
00:36:30,939 --> 00:36:32,732
"Right, I came to the US.

938
00:36:32,816 --> 00:36:35,360
I'm here for a match. Oh, right!

939
00:36:35,443 --> 00:36:36,277
What?

940
00:36:37,362 --> 00:36:38,655
The match is over?"

941
00:36:38,822 --> 00:36:41,116
Then, I looked at the screen,

942
00:36:41,199 --> 00:36:43,410
and saw footage I didn't recognize.

943
00:36:43,785 --> 00:36:44,661
"Did I just lose?"

944
00:36:45,537 --> 00:36:47,247
That's when I realized I'd lost.

945
00:36:49,082 --> 00:36:49,999
So...

946
00:36:50,542 --> 00:36:53,044
What I was thinking at that moment,

947
00:36:53,128 --> 00:36:54,587
to be honest,

948
00:36:54,671 --> 00:36:56,464
wasn't "Oh, no! I lost."

949
00:36:56,548 --> 00:36:58,633
I only knocked people out before.

950
00:36:58,717 --> 00:37:00,427
- But I'd never been knocked out.
- So...

951
00:37:00,510 --> 00:37:02,220
So I didn't know how it felt.

952
00:37:02,303 --> 00:37:03,680
I was vaguely scared.

953
00:37:03,763 --> 00:37:04,723
- Of being KO'd.
- Yes.

954
00:37:04,806 --> 00:37:07,100
I wondered if it would hurt.

955
00:37:07,183 --> 00:37:08,143
I get it.

956
00:37:08,727 --> 00:37:11,146
But actually,
you don't really feel anything.

957
00:37:11,646 --> 00:37:13,440
You can't feel anything at all.

958
00:37:13,523 --> 00:37:15,108
It doesn't even hurt.

959
00:37:15,942 --> 00:37:19,154
You can only remember the moment
before taking the blow.

960
00:37:19,237 --> 00:37:20,321
And then, nothing.

961
00:37:20,405 --> 00:37:21,990
I was like, "I felt nothing.

962
00:37:22,073 --> 00:37:23,283
Why was I so scared?

963
00:37:23,742 --> 00:37:24,951
Why was I so worried?"

964
00:37:25,034 --> 00:37:26,619
I wanted to remember that.

965
00:37:27,412 --> 00:37:29,706
- After that--
- Wait.

966
00:37:29,789 --> 00:37:32,333
- You learned from failure.
- Right? Exactly.

967
00:37:32,417 --> 00:37:34,586
I didn't have to worry about being KO'd.

968
00:37:35,128 --> 00:37:36,671
I open my eyes, and it's over.

969
00:37:36,755 --> 00:37:39,048
As long as I'm awake,
I'll fight my heart out.

970
00:37:40,258 --> 00:37:42,552
- I think that's what I learned.
- I see.

971
00:37:42,635 --> 00:37:45,764
Many people will want to hear
about your game with Erick Silva.

972
00:37:45,847 --> 00:37:48,224
JUNGLE FIGHT WELTERWEIGHT CHAMPION

973
00:37:48,308 --> 00:37:52,061
A UFC FIGHTER KNOWN AT THE TIME
FOR HIS DYNAMIC STYLE

974
00:37:52,145 --> 00:37:53,646
Erick Silva is world-class.

975
00:37:53,730 --> 00:37:55,440
- His games are exciting and fun.
- Right.

976
00:37:55,523 --> 00:37:57,066
- He was hyped.
- Right.

977
00:37:57,150 --> 00:37:59,861
They wanted to give him a win,

978
00:37:59,944 --> 00:38:02,322
so they sent me to Brazil.

979
00:38:02,405 --> 00:38:04,866
SET UP FOR HIM TO LOSE
It was a home game for him.

980
00:38:04,949 --> 00:38:06,117
- That's right.
- Yes.

981
00:38:06,201 --> 00:38:07,869
I read in an article

982
00:38:07,952 --> 00:38:09,871
that you were about to be expelled

983
00:38:09,954 --> 00:38:11,372
- when the game was set up.
- Right.

984
00:38:11,456 --> 00:38:12,957
Some articles were saying that.

985
00:38:14,209 --> 00:38:15,502
My matches were boring for years.

986
00:38:15,877 --> 00:38:17,796
I did well and kept winning,

987
00:38:17,879 --> 00:38:19,547
- but my matches were boring.
- Right.

988
00:38:19,631 --> 00:38:23,051
They said I'd be kicked out for that.

989
00:38:23,134 --> 00:38:24,677
Of course, I get it.

990
00:38:24,761 --> 00:38:27,096
- Fans keep the UFC alive.
- Right.

991
00:38:27,180 --> 00:38:29,390
Fans want to watch an exciting game.

992
00:38:29,474 --> 00:38:31,267
I understand that 100%.

993
00:38:31,351 --> 00:38:34,145
So, when I was
on the verge of being kicked out,

994
00:38:34,687 --> 00:38:36,481
rather than being sad and giving up,

995
00:38:36,564 --> 00:38:39,609
I thought, "Okay, if you want a spectacle,
I'll give you one.

996
00:38:39,692 --> 00:38:40,735
I can do that.

997
00:38:40,819 --> 00:38:42,821
I wasn't scared of taking punches.

998
00:38:42,904 --> 00:38:44,447
I just wanted to win.

999
00:38:44,531 --> 00:38:46,115
I fought like that to not lose.

1000
00:38:46,199 --> 00:38:47,575
Since I might get kicked out,

1001
00:38:47,951 --> 00:38:48,952
let me show you."

1002
00:38:49,369 --> 00:38:51,955
Erick Silva had a lot of fans.

1003
00:38:52,038 --> 00:38:53,957
- The UFC was pushing him a lot.
- Right.

1004
00:38:54,040 --> 00:38:56,501
He probably didn't expect me
to think this way.

1005
00:38:56,584 --> 00:38:58,628
He probably expected wrestling.

1006
00:38:58,711 --> 00:39:00,505
- He must've analyzed you.
- Right.

1007
00:39:00,588 --> 00:39:02,757
So I fought him in Brazil.

1008
00:39:02,841 --> 00:39:04,175
From the start,

1009
00:39:04,259 --> 00:39:07,262
I didn't care about taking punches.
I just went right in.

1010
00:39:07,345 --> 00:39:10,056
This was a fighter who was like a lion,

1011
00:39:10,598 --> 00:39:13,017
but he was completely fazed.

1012
00:39:13,893 --> 00:39:16,145
He kept backing away.

1013
00:39:16,229 --> 00:39:17,772
- He didn't expect it.
- He didn't.

1014
00:39:17,856 --> 00:39:18,982
So I pushed him

1015
00:39:19,065 --> 00:39:20,316
until he hit the fence.

1016
00:39:20,400 --> 00:39:22,026
What was the atmosphere like?

1017
00:39:22,110 --> 00:39:23,570
It was crazy.

1018
00:39:23,653 --> 00:39:26,739
The Brazilian fans were cheering.

1019
00:39:26,823 --> 00:39:28,032
It was so loud.

1020
00:39:28,116 --> 00:39:30,326
Whenever I was hit, they went crazy.

1021
00:39:30,410 --> 00:39:32,662
They went wild.

1022
00:39:32,745 --> 00:39:35,248
They booed me when I did well.

1023
00:39:35,874 --> 00:39:38,334
He was struggling, so I kept going at him.

1024
00:39:38,418 --> 00:39:41,379
I was ready to knock him out.

1025
00:39:42,422 --> 00:39:44,507
At one point, out of the blue,

1026
00:39:44,591 --> 00:39:46,050
I heard a voice in my head.

1027
00:39:46,217 --> 00:39:48,720
It's like someone was saying,
"Throw a punch!"

1028
00:39:48,803 --> 00:39:50,096
I heard that in my head.

1029
00:39:50,179 --> 00:39:51,723
So I did throw a punch.

1030
00:39:52,974 --> 00:39:54,642
I wasn't even looking ahead.

1031
00:39:55,310 --> 00:39:56,936
I was also tired.

1032
00:39:57,020 --> 00:39:58,605
- I threw it--
- You were tired.

1033
00:39:58,688 --> 00:39:59,981
I was tired already.

1034
00:40:00,064 --> 00:40:01,441
So I just threw the punch,

1035
00:40:02,358 --> 00:40:04,277
but at that moment,

1036
00:40:04,360 --> 00:40:07,113
Erick Silva also threw a punch.

1037
00:40:07,196 --> 00:40:08,615
So it became a counterpunch.

1038
00:40:08,698 --> 00:40:11,659
TURNING AN OPPONENT'S ATTACK AGAINST THEM
The punch that I threw.

1039
00:40:12,076 --> 00:40:14,412
I looked up, and I didn't see him.

1040
00:40:14,495 --> 00:40:15,413
He was...

1041
00:40:15,496 --> 00:40:17,123
I still remember it vividly.

1042
00:40:17,206 --> 00:40:18,666
- You were so tired.
- Yes.

1043
00:40:19,375 --> 00:40:20,585
So, I didn't see him.

1044
00:40:20,668 --> 00:40:23,296
He staggered before he collapsed.

1045
00:40:23,379 --> 00:40:25,214
I thought he slipped.

1046
00:40:25,298 --> 00:40:26,799
I didn't know I hit him here.

1047
00:40:27,300 --> 00:40:28,593
So I hit him again.

1048
00:40:29,636 --> 00:40:32,138
That became quite controversial

1049
00:40:32,430 --> 00:40:34,724
- since I hit him after he was KO'd.
- I see.

1050
00:40:35,141 --> 00:40:36,684
- That's a general rule.
- Right.

1051
00:40:36,768 --> 00:40:37,810
Don't hit where it hurts.

1052
00:40:37,894 --> 00:40:40,396
I felt bad about it
and apologized to him afterward.

1053
00:40:40,480 --> 00:40:42,899
I met him recently and apologized.

1054
00:40:42,982 --> 00:40:44,359
JANUARY 2026
That explains it.

1055
00:40:44,442 --> 00:40:46,235
I really had no idea.

1056
00:40:46,319 --> 00:40:49,530
Before I threw that punch,
I was just getting hit.

1057
00:40:49,614 --> 00:40:51,032
So the crowd was going wild.

1058
00:40:51,574 --> 00:40:55,453
They were cheering and applauding.

1059
00:40:55,536 --> 00:40:58,915
They were doing their cheer.

1060
00:40:58,998 --> 00:41:01,751
When I punched him,
it was like someone hit mute.

1061
00:41:03,544 --> 00:41:05,129
They went silent.

1062
00:41:05,213 --> 00:41:06,547
That's how I won.

1063
00:41:06,631 --> 00:41:09,133
I'm pretty good at damage control.

1064
00:41:09,217 --> 00:41:13,513
I got down on my knees immediately
and started bowing in all directions.

1065
00:41:13,596 --> 00:41:15,098
I bowed politely.

1066
00:41:15,181 --> 00:41:17,141
My staff and I got too excited.

1067
00:41:17,225 --> 00:41:18,851
We thought I'd lose, but I won.

1068
00:41:19,227 --> 00:41:21,270
While we were cheering, I thought,

1069
00:41:21,354 --> 00:41:22,689
"Right, I'm in Brazil."

1070
00:41:22,772 --> 00:41:25,358
So I went to the center
and started bowing.

1071
00:41:25,441 --> 00:41:27,527
The next day,

1072
00:41:27,610 --> 00:41:31,447
I went to a sports shop and bought
a Brazilian soccer uniform to wear around.

1073
00:41:32,031 --> 00:41:33,282
I had it on until I left.

1074
00:41:33,366 --> 00:41:35,576
- Just in case.
- You were scared.

1075
00:41:35,660 --> 00:41:36,911
Just in case.

1076
00:41:37,578 --> 00:41:40,748
Dana White, the UFC's CEO,
was going to fire me,

1077
00:41:40,832 --> 00:41:43,251
but after that, he said it was a good game

1078
00:41:43,334 --> 00:41:44,460
and renewed my contract.

1079
00:41:44,544 --> 00:41:46,754
- Was the bonus huge?
- I did get a bonus.

1080
00:41:46,838 --> 00:41:49,966
That's how my career got extended.

1081
00:41:50,049 --> 00:41:52,844
You could say the game with Erick Silva

1082
00:41:52,927 --> 00:41:55,179
put you in the spotlight with MMA fans

1083
00:41:55,263 --> 00:41:56,431
- worldwide.
- Yes.

1084
00:41:56,514 --> 00:41:58,349
But you were at a disadvantage.

1085
00:41:58,433 --> 00:42:00,643
Before that big game,
I heard Lee Jeong-won...

1086
00:42:00,727 --> 00:42:02,687
LEE JEONG-WON
DONG-HYUN'S MMA TEAM COACH

1087
00:42:02,770 --> 00:42:06,399
...helped you a lot mindset-wise
with his positivity.

1088
00:42:06,482 --> 00:42:08,568
As the game gets closer,

1089
00:42:08,901 --> 00:42:10,945
I think your mindset is more important

1090
00:42:11,029 --> 00:42:12,864
than your training.

1091
00:42:12,947 --> 00:42:16,951
I was going to the other side of the world

1092
00:42:17,618 --> 00:42:20,538
for a game where my losing
would help the competition.

1093
00:42:20,621 --> 00:42:22,290
That was the setting.

1094
00:42:22,665 --> 00:42:24,417
Lee Jeong-won was by my side,

1095
00:42:24,500 --> 00:42:27,086
helping me maintain composure.

1096
00:42:27,587 --> 00:42:31,591
"Ruining a party is easier
than having a successful one."

1097
00:42:31,674 --> 00:42:32,842
Ruining a party is easy.

1098
00:42:32,925 --> 00:42:34,552
You just flip the table.

1099
00:42:34,635 --> 00:42:35,970
- That was the vibe.
- I see.

1100
00:42:36,054 --> 00:42:37,972
On the other hand, my opponent

1101
00:42:38,056 --> 00:42:40,433
would be under a lot of pressure to win.

1102
00:42:40,516 --> 00:42:43,227
Psychologically, I was at an advantage.

1103
00:42:43,311 --> 00:42:45,063
That's what I thought as I went in.

1104
00:42:45,146 --> 00:42:48,316
I didn't know what was actually
on his mind, but it didn't matter.

1105
00:42:48,399 --> 00:42:50,359
But that was just our mindset.

1106
00:42:50,860 --> 00:42:54,363
Also, right next to the hotel
we were staying in,

1107
00:42:54,530 --> 00:42:56,616
- there was construction going on.
- I see.

1108
00:42:56,991 --> 00:42:59,494
- I could hear all kinds of noises.
- It was noisy.

1109
00:42:59,577 --> 00:43:00,953
It was so noisy.

1110
00:43:01,037 --> 00:43:02,747
But I had to get used to that.

1111
00:43:02,830 --> 00:43:06,501
Because the crowd was going to boo me.

1112
00:43:06,584 --> 00:43:08,211
- Right.
- I had to get used to it.

1113
00:43:08,294 --> 00:43:10,296
He kept saying I should think positively.

1114
00:43:10,379 --> 00:43:12,256
He was ridiculously positive.

1115
00:43:12,340 --> 00:43:14,467
- He helped you think of the noise as boos
- Right.

1116
00:43:14,550 --> 00:43:16,803
- so you could use it to train your mind.
- Yes.

1117
00:43:16,886 --> 00:43:19,555
"The excavator is helping us."
That's how we took it in.

1118
00:43:19,639 --> 00:43:21,307
- Right. That's the power of positivity.
- Yes.

1119
00:43:21,390 --> 00:43:23,976
- We turned everything that way.
- Say it's raining.

1120
00:43:24,060 --> 00:43:25,103
If it's raining,

1121
00:43:25,186 --> 00:43:27,855
because the weather's bad on game day,

1122
00:43:27,939 --> 00:43:30,399
my opponent would feel down.

1123
00:43:30,566 --> 00:43:31,526
"That helps me."

1124
00:43:31,609 --> 00:43:33,152
"I'm feeling fine."

1125
00:43:33,611 --> 00:43:35,363
My opponent's mindset doesn't matter.

1126
00:43:35,446 --> 00:43:36,906
He'll get wet in the rain,

1127
00:43:36,989 --> 00:43:38,658
which will put him on edge.

1128
00:43:38,741 --> 00:43:40,493
He'll feel off when he walks in.

1129
00:43:40,952 --> 00:43:42,411
- Like that.
- "I like rain."

1130
00:43:42,495 --> 00:43:44,330
"I like rain. I feel fine."

1131
00:43:44,580 --> 00:43:46,874
I don't care
how my opponent actually feels.

1132
00:43:46,958 --> 00:43:48,668
That was how I did it.

1133
00:43:48,751 --> 00:43:51,379
In any difficult situation,
you had a positive mindset.

1134
00:43:51,462 --> 00:43:54,382
It was always,
"That got the bad luck out of the way."

1135
00:43:54,465 --> 00:43:56,050
Your mindset is what's most important.

1136
00:43:56,134 --> 00:43:57,593
- It is.
- I see here,

1137
00:43:57,969 --> 00:43:59,846
- that you wrote a book.
- I did.

1138
00:43:59,929 --> 00:44:01,180
- You did.
- Yes.

1139
00:44:01,264 --> 00:44:02,682
- Let me bring it.
- Okay.

1140
00:44:02,765 --> 00:44:04,016
It was hard to find.

1141
00:44:04,100 --> 00:44:05,518
We didn't print that many.

1142
00:44:06,686 --> 00:44:09,772
It's been over 13 years,
but we only printed once.

1143
00:44:09,856 --> 00:44:11,732
- Here it is.
- I see.

1144
00:44:12,525 --> 00:44:14,152
<i>- Kim Dong-hyun's Mentality Class.</i>
- Yes.

1145
00:44:14,235 --> 00:44:15,319
- Right?
- Yes.

1146
00:44:15,403 --> 00:44:17,530
It's so old. It's looking yellow.

1147
00:44:17,989 --> 00:44:21,200
"Five rules for a stronger mentality
that make a confident life."

1148
00:44:21,284 --> 00:44:22,910
UFC FIGHTER KIM DONG-HYUN'S SECRET GUIDE
TO BUILDING A STRONG MENTALITY

1149
00:44:22,994 --> 00:44:25,872
"Learn from a fighter
how to be stronger mentally."

1150
00:44:26,080 --> 00:44:28,374
It's a pretty thick book,

1151
00:44:28,457 --> 00:44:29,375
but it's a 30-minute read.

1152
00:44:29,458 --> 00:44:30,835
The letters are huge.

1153
00:44:31,627 --> 00:44:32,837
They really are.

1154
00:44:32,920 --> 00:44:34,505
- It's so easy to read.
- It is.

1155
00:44:34,589 --> 00:44:36,549
To make it this thick,

1156
00:44:38,134 --> 00:44:40,887
we put in spaces to write notes in.

1157
00:44:41,512 --> 00:44:43,681
And we used a huge font.

1158
00:44:43,764 --> 00:44:45,057
FOOTNOTE: THE FONT IS HUGE

1159
00:44:45,141 --> 00:44:46,350
As big as it can get.

1160
00:44:46,434 --> 00:44:49,562
The pages also have very wide margins.

1161
00:44:49,645 --> 00:44:51,314
Based on your experience,

1162
00:44:51,606 --> 00:44:53,983
- you wanted to convey to the readers
- Yes.

1163
00:44:54,066 --> 00:44:56,235
the power of positivity.

1164
00:44:56,319 --> 00:44:59,572
Just like the viral mentality
of IVE's Won-young.

1165
00:44:59,739 --> 00:45:00,990
- The "Dong-hyun mindset."
- Yes.

1166
00:45:01,073 --> 00:45:02,742
- It became a meme.
- I suppose.

1167
00:45:02,825 --> 00:45:03,951
<i>What a great workout.</i>

1168
00:45:04,035 --> 00:45:05,244
<i>Terrific workout today.</i>

1169
00:45:05,328 --> 00:45:07,079
<i>What a great workout.</i>

1170
00:45:07,163 --> 00:45:09,081
<i>You're not saying it,</i>
<i>but I know you're stressed right now.</i>

1171
00:45:09,165 --> 00:45:10,791
BECAME VIRAL DUE TO REPEATED ENCOURAGEMENT
<i>He's going to be stressed after.</i>

1172
00:45:10,875 --> 00:45:12,168
<i>It's a great experience.</i>

1173
00:45:12,251 --> 00:45:13,419
<i>I envy you.</i>

1174
00:45:13,502 --> 00:45:16,297
I don't know how that became viral.

1175
00:45:16,380 --> 00:45:19,175
That's just what I've always been saying
while training.

1176
00:45:19,258 --> 00:45:21,844
It strangely got attention this year.

1177
00:45:21,928 --> 00:45:23,763
It was unexpected.

1178
00:45:23,846 --> 00:45:27,808
I don't know why it became a meme.

1179
00:45:27,892 --> 00:45:30,394
You were just encouraging
younger fighters.

1180
00:45:30,478 --> 00:45:32,688
It's just what athletes say
while training.

1181
00:45:32,772 --> 00:45:35,483
"This is going to help you grow so much."

1182
00:45:35,566 --> 00:45:37,151
"This is a great workout."

1183
00:45:37,235 --> 00:45:39,654
"You're learning so much."
That was my mindset.

1184
00:45:39,737 --> 00:45:40,905
And the stress thing

1185
00:45:40,988 --> 00:45:42,490
- is what they need to grow.
- Exactly.

1186
00:45:42,573 --> 00:45:45,201
The fact that you're stressed
at that moment

1187
00:45:45,284 --> 00:45:46,827
is the most important thing.

1188
00:45:46,911 --> 00:45:48,996
After you break a bone,

1189
00:45:49,080 --> 00:45:51,249
it becomes harder
and it never breaks again.

1190
00:45:54,126 --> 00:45:55,920
Because you're an athlete,

1191
00:45:56,003 --> 00:45:58,172
- you've broken a bone before, right?
- Yes.

1192
00:45:58,256 --> 00:45:59,423
After it breaks,

1193
00:45:59,507 --> 00:46:01,092
- it heals with time.
- Right.

1194
00:46:01,175 --> 00:46:02,510
And it becomes harder?

1195
00:46:02,593 --> 00:46:04,011
It becomes harder.

1196
00:46:04,095 --> 00:46:05,263
Why?

1197
00:46:05,471 --> 00:46:07,932
Isn't it because the bone produces fluid?

1198
00:46:11,227 --> 00:46:13,020
Fluid. No?

1199
00:46:14,355 --> 00:46:17,066
I don't know the exact medical facts.

1200
00:46:17,608 --> 00:46:19,151
I just believe so.

1201
00:46:20,236 --> 00:46:22,071
My bones never broke again
after they've healed.

1202
00:46:22,154 --> 00:46:24,365
FOOTNOTE:
IT SEEMS TO BE HIS PERSONAL OPINION

1203
00:46:24,448 --> 00:46:25,825
Where did you hear this?

1204
00:46:25,908 --> 00:46:27,535
Isn't there a saying?

1205
00:46:27,618 --> 00:46:29,870
"What doesn't kill you
makes you stronger!"

1206
00:46:33,666 --> 00:46:34,542
Okay.

1207
00:46:34,625 --> 00:46:36,002
Should I ask ChatGPT?

1208
00:46:36,085 --> 00:46:38,212
- I think it's time we wrap up.
- Okay.

1209
00:46:38,838 --> 00:46:41,674
WE LEARNED
THAT WE CAN'T CONTROL OTHER PEOPLE

1210
00:46:41,757 --> 00:46:43,342
OR WHAT HAPPENS TO US

1211
00:46:43,426 --> 00:46:45,386
BUT WE CAN CONTROL HOW WE ACT

1212
00:46:45,469 --> 00:46:47,346
WE ALSO LEARNED THAT HOW YOU REACT

1213
00:46:47,430 --> 00:46:49,765
IS MORE IMPORTANT
THAN WHAT ACTUALLY HAPPENS

1214
00:46:49,849 --> 00:46:51,726
FROM <i>DON'T EAT THE MARSHMALLOW YET!</i>

1215
00:46:51,809 --> 00:46:55,313
What kind of person
do you dream of being in the future?

1216
00:46:55,396 --> 00:46:56,856
Becoming the world's greatest

1217
00:46:56,939 --> 00:46:58,649
among the best fighters is good,

1218
00:46:58,733 --> 00:47:00,985
but I want to take care of myself

1219
00:47:01,694 --> 00:47:03,029
even after 50 years old.

1220
00:47:03,112 --> 00:47:04,697
It's not easy for an athlete

1221
00:47:04,780 --> 00:47:06,532
to be in shape after 50 years old.

1222
00:47:06,615 --> 00:47:09,201
I want to be as in shape
as I was when I was a pro

1223
00:47:09,285 --> 00:47:13,039
and consistently maintain my performance.

1224
00:47:13,122 --> 00:47:16,459
I think that's also very meaningful.

1225
00:47:16,542 --> 00:47:18,669
Diligence deserves an award.

1226
00:47:19,211 --> 00:47:20,338
- I see.
- Yes.

1227
00:47:20,421 --> 00:47:23,132
- I've been meaning to ask.
- Okay.

1228
00:47:23,215 --> 00:47:25,009
I want to know how much

1229
00:47:25,092 --> 00:47:27,595
you'll pay for my book.

1230
00:47:27,678 --> 00:47:29,638
- All right, this book...
- Here.

1231
00:47:34,935 --> 00:47:37,438
- Okay, I've set the price.
- Great.

1232
00:47:37,813 --> 00:47:39,273
The price

1233
00:47:39,565 --> 00:47:42,026
- of your favorite book is...
- Okay.

1234
00:47:42,109 --> 00:47:43,527
HODONG'S BOOKSHOP

1235
00:47:44,195 --> 00:47:45,488
<i>The Archer!</i>

1236
00:47:45,571 --> 00:47:46,781
What?

1237
00:47:47,198 --> 00:47:48,908
- Here you go.
- What is this?

1238
00:47:48,991 --> 00:47:50,493
MASTERING ATTITUDE AND MINDSET IN LIFE
THROUGH ARCHERY TRAINING

1239
00:47:50,576 --> 00:47:52,745
- This is from <i>The Archer.</i>
- Okay.

1240
00:47:52,828 --> 00:47:56,290
"When you're stiff due to fear of failure,
shoot without hesitation.

1241
00:47:57,083 --> 00:47:58,751
Even if your arrow misses,

1242
00:47:58,834 --> 00:48:01,837
you'll learn
how to control it better next time."

1243
00:48:02,088 --> 00:48:04,882
What a wonderful quote.

1244
00:48:04,965 --> 00:48:06,801
I think this book suits you.

1245
00:48:06,884 --> 00:48:10,513
Someone who learns from every failure
and constantly moves forward.

1246
00:48:10,888 --> 00:48:13,974
Someone who shines bright
with their passion and positivity.

1247
00:48:14,058 --> 00:48:17,937
Your life resembles the main character's
from Coelho's book, <i>The Archer</i>.

1248
00:48:18,020 --> 00:48:20,189
- I, Hocrates,
- Yes?

1249
00:48:20,272 --> 00:48:22,400
- will be rooting for you.
- Thank you.

1250
00:48:22,566 --> 00:48:23,567
I'll give it a read.

1251
00:48:24,985 --> 00:48:26,612
- Dong-hyun.
- Yes.

1252
00:48:26,695 --> 00:48:28,739
You're still puffy
from the skincare procedure.

1253
00:48:28,823 --> 00:48:30,032
I'm sorry.

1254
00:48:30,116 --> 00:48:31,992
How was your visit to our bookshop?

1255
00:48:32,076 --> 00:48:35,621
I've almost never had
a sincere talk about my life like this.

1256
00:48:35,704 --> 00:48:37,540
- I see.
- I enjoyed doing that.

1257
00:48:37,623 --> 00:48:39,500
The cutest neighborhood in the world.

1258
00:48:39,583 --> 00:48:40,459
- Yes.
- Where is it?

1259
00:48:40,918 --> 00:48:42,670
Kangho-dong... town.

1260
00:48:43,587 --> 00:48:44,755
Right? Kangho-dong town.

1261
00:48:44,839 --> 00:48:47,466
We heard about Kim Dong-hyun's tasty life.

1262
00:48:47,550 --> 00:48:49,468
That was a great read!

1263
00:48:50,386 --> 00:48:52,805
NEXT GUEST
PORK BONE SOUP?

1264
00:48:52,888 --> 00:48:54,723
- That's right.
- Right?

1265
00:48:54,807 --> 00:48:55,891
Ok Dong-sik.

1266
00:48:55,975 --> 00:48:58,018
<i>On the Times' list of NYC's best dishes.</i>

1267
00:48:58,102 --> 00:49:00,020
A Michelin Bib Gourmand
for eight consecutive years.

1268
00:49:00,104 --> 00:49:01,439
This cabbage tastes better than the meat.

1269
00:49:02,815 --> 00:49:03,983
You make delectable conversation.

1270
00:49:04,066 --> 00:49:06,861
- Their president is always late.
- The president?

1271
00:49:06,944 --> 00:49:09,196
Most were against me.
"I told you so," but no.

1272
00:49:09,280 --> 00:49:10,114
I told you so.

1273
00:49:10,197 --> 00:49:11,949
THE STORY OMAKASE IS OPEN

1274
00:49:12,032 --> 00:49:13,784
WHO IS KIM DONG-HYUN?

1275
00:49:13,868 --> 00:49:20,875
A PERSON WHO BELIEVES IN TRAINING
MORE THAN RESULTS AND KEEPS GROWING

1276
00:49:44,940 --> 00:49:46,942
Subtitle translation by Cayle Kim
